some tall shelves

260
00:27:53,792 --> 00:27:55,167
and cabinetry installed.

261
00:27:56,500 --> 00:27:59,417
Maybe make him a ladder
with little wheels on it.

262
00:27:59,500 --> 00:28:01,833
You know? Like you'd see
in a real library.

263
00:28:03,250 --> 00:28:04,875
He's a voracious reader.

264
00:28:04,958 --> 00:28:06,833
Yeah, we can make you
something like that.

265
00:28:08,125 --> 00:28:11,333
Let me have Audrey come down
and keep an eye on the place

266
00:28:11,417 --> 00:28:13,250
and I'll pull the van around.

267
00:28:13,333 --> 00:28:15,167
- Fantastic.
- I'll be right back.

268
00:28:33,458 --> 00:28:34,958
They pay you well?

269
00:28:36,250 --> 00:28:37,583
On the last job...

270
00:28:39,083 --> 00:28:40,083
they paid okay.

271
00:28:41,292 --> 00:28:43,458
Took on a lot of pieces,
though.

272
00:28:43,542 --> 00:28:44,792
They kept adding to the order.

273
00:28:44,875 --> 00:28:46,542
Even at a discount,
it adds up.

274
00:28:48,292 --> 00:28:50,250
His old man got flush

275
00:28:51,250 --> 00:28:53,167
adapting production techniques

276
00:28:53,250 --> 00:28:56,958
to expedite the manufacturing
of cargo ships during the war.

277
00:29:00,250 --> 00:29:02,000
Christ, is this guy
trying to shake us?

278
00:29:03,167 --> 00:29:04,792
Thinks it's a drag race?

279
00:29:05,625 --> 00:29:07,250
Hey, come on, already!

280
00:29:15,375 --> 00:29:17,708
Stay right until
you see the main house.

281
00:29:17,792 --> 00:29:19,458
You can park
wherever you like.

282
00:29:50,042 --> 00:29:51,917
<i>I do appreciate
you coming out here</i>

283
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:53,667
on such short notice,
gentlemen.

284
00:29:53,750 --> 00:29:56,208
Father is away
only until next Friday.

285
00:29:56,292 --> 00:29:57,958
I was anxious
to pin this down.

286
00:29:58,042 --> 00:30:00,542
Ah, it's no
inconvenience for us, chief.

287
00:30:01,875 --> 00:30:03,042
It's your lucky day, too,

288
00:30:03,125 --> 00:30:07,583
'cause my cousin here
is a licensed architect,

289
00:30:07,667 --> 00:30:09,250
a specialist in renovations.

290
00:30:09,333 --> 00:30:12,958
He even designed a library
back at home before.

291
00:30:13,042 --> 00:30:15,000
Right? A whole city library.

292
00:30:15,083 --> 00:30:16,458
What city is that?

293
00:30:18,333 --> 00:30:22,417
- Budapest.
- I see. Never been.

294
00:30:24,458 --> 00:30:26,000
Don't mind the mess.

295
00:30:33,667 --> 00:30:36,458
I know.
It's terribly dated, isn't it?

296
00:30:39,375 --> 00:30:42,833
I'm thinking
shelves up to the ceiling

297
00:30:42,917 --> 00:30:44,625
and some good reading lamps.

298
00:30:45,458 --> 00:30:47,625
Perhaps some wall fixtures
that extend.

299
00:30:48,833 --> 00:30:51,125
Father always keeps
the curtains drawn.

300
00:30:52,125 --> 00:30:54,750
It is to protect the books
from the sunlight.

301
00:30:55,792 --> 00:30:57,125
We are south-facing here.

302
00:30:58,583 --> 00:30:59,583
Sure.

303
00:31:01,083 --> 00:31:03,583
- What's your budget?
- What's your estimate?

304
00:31:04,292 --> 00:31:05,875
Depends on the materials.

305
00:31:06,917 --> 00:31:10,542
Well...
make it of reasonable quality.

306
00:31:11,667 --> 00:31:14,458
Perhaps a nice place for him
to sit and read as well?

307
00:31:15,583 --> 00:31:18,542
A good chair or a bench
for him against the window.

308
00:31:27,125 --> 00:31:29,500
You want for us
to replace that?

309
00:31:30,708 --> 00:31:32,375
if there's time, why not?

310
00:31:33,333 --> 00:31:36,875
A branch fell on it during
a nasty storm last summer.

311
00:31:38,083 --> 00:31:40,750
Tropical depression,
I think they called it.

312
00:31:42,833 --> 00:31:45,208
Keep it below $1,000, can you?

313
00:31:46,042 --> 00:31:47,625
My sister and I
are splitting it.

314
00:31:48,500 --> 00:31:50,750
I don't want
any unexpected add-ons.

315
00:31:51,792 --> 00:31:54,833
Don't worry.
We'll come in on budget.

316
00:31:56,000 --> 00:31:58,083
You want all this done
by next Friday, right?

317
00:31:58,167 --> 00:31:59,792
Thursday night, preferably.

318
00:32:00,667 --> 00:32:02,125
I can't be here
during the week,

319
00:32:02,208 --> 00:32:03,583
but the staff can let you in.

320
00:32:04,250 --> 00:32:05,625
If anything comes up,

321
00:32:05,708 --> 00:32:07,500
have them ring me
at the office.

322
00:32:07,583 --> 00:32:10,542
If to be finished on Thursday,
we need extra hands.

323
00:32:11,458 --> 00:32:13,708
Including materials, glass...

324
00:32:16,458 --> 00:32:17,792
it's $2,000.

325
00:32:25,333 --> 00:32:27,708
♪ <i>East is east
And west is west</i> ♪

326
00:32:27,792 --> 00:32:30,750
♪ <i>And the wrong one
I have chose</i> ♪

327
00:32:30,833 --> 00:32:33,167
♪ <i>Let's go where
I'll keep on wear in</i>' ♪

328
00:32:33,250 --> 00:32:36,083
♪ <i>Those frills and flowers
And buttons and bows</i> ♪

329
00:32:36,167 --> 00:32:41,125
♪ <i>Rings and things
And buttons and bows</i> ♪

330
00:32:41,208 --> 00:32:43,708
♪ <i>Don't bury me
In this prairie</i> ♪

331
00:32:43,792 --> 00:32:46,583
♪ <i>Take me where
The cement grows</i> ♪

332
00:32:46,667 --> 00:32:49,167
♪ <i>Let's move down
To some big town</i> ♪

333
00:32:49,250 --> 00:32:52,208
♪ <i>Where they love a gal
By the cut of her clothes</i> ♪

334
00:32:52,292 --> 00:32:57,083
♪ <i>And I'll stand out
In buttons and bows</i> ♪

335
00:32:57,167 --> 00:32:59,875
♪ <i>I'll love you in buckskin</i> ♪

336
00:32:59,958 --> 00:33:02,417
♪ <i>And skirts
That I've homespun</i> ♪

337
00:33:02,500 --> 00:33:05,250
♪ <i>But I'll love you longer
Stronger where</i> ♪

338
00:33:05,333 --> 00:33:07,833
♪ <i>Your friends
Don't tote a gun</i> ♪

339
00:33:07,917 --> 00:33:10,500
♪ <i>My bones denounce
The buckboard bounce</i> ♪

340
00:33:10,583 --> 00:33:13,458
♪ <i>And the cactus
Hurts my toes</i> ♪

341
00:33:13,542 --> 00:33:15,500
Flip it for the other side.

342
00:33:18,208 --> 00:33:19,625
Ah, okay.

343
00:33:19,708 --> 00:33:21,750
You should have seen him...

344
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:23,083
...talking up the prices.

345
00:33:23,167 --> 00:33:25,250
I was ready to settle at 450.

346
00:33:25,333 --> 00:33:26,833
- I was not doing that.
- You were.

347
00:33:26,917 --> 00:33:29,333
I was not. I was telling him
how much it will cost.

348
00:33:29,417 --> 00:33:33,625
No, I... I thought he was
going to blow it for us.

349
00:33:33,708 --> 00:33:35,792
<i>But you held your ground.</i>

350
00:33:37,000 --> 00:33:39,167
<i>And that's what makes you
professional.</i>

351
00:33:41,750 --> 00:33:44,583
<i>I hope it is not only that.</i>

352
00:33:45,958 --> 00:33:47,125
She's so beautiful.

353
00:33:48,333 --> 00:33:50,583
Look at her.
She has that red dress

354
00:33:50,667 --> 00:33:54,083
and it's the same as...
color as her lips.

355
00:33:57,333 --> 00:33:58,542
Dance with her.

356
00:34:00,292 --> 00:34:01,792
Dance with her.

357
00:34:01,875 --> 00:34:03,583
- I don't want to dance.
- Go on.

358
00:34:03,667 --> 00:34:05,458
- I don't... I don't...
- Come on.

359
00:34:05,542 --> 00:34:07,167
I don't want to.
No, thank you.

360
00:34:07,250 --> 00:34:08,333
He doesn't want to.

361
00:34:08,417 --> 00:34:10,917
Don't make her...
Don't make her wait.

362
00:34:11,000 --> 00:34:12,000
Dance with her.

363
00:34:13,792 --> 00:34:16,875
It's her favorite song, man.
It's her favorite song.

364
00:34:17,875 --> 00:34:20,542
We'll do it together,
I'll show you the steps.

365
00:34:20,625 --> 00:34:21,875
Dance with her.

366
00:34:22,875 --> 00:34:24,250
Dance with her,
dance with her.

367
00:34:24,333 --> 00:34:25,375
She wants you to.

368
00:34:25,458 --> 00:34:27,292
- It's her favorite song.
- Attila.

369
00:34:27,375 --> 00:34:28,792
It's her favorite song.

370
00:34:29,792 --> 00:34:31,875
Go on. Dance with her.

371
00:34:31,958 --> 00:34:33,167
Don't...

372
00:34:33,250 --> 00:34:34,750
She's waiting for you.

373
00:34:34,833 --> 00:34:36,833
- She's waiting for you.
- Okay, all right.

374
00:34:39,083 --> 00:34:41,250
All right, all right.

375
00:34:41,333 --> 00:34:43,792
- Don't.
- Yeah!

376
00:34:43,875 --> 00:34:45,083
- You're an idiot.
- Go on!

377
00:34:45,167 --> 00:34:46,250
Get off.

378
00:34:48,500 --> 00:34:50,917
♪ <i>Someone kind</i> ♪

379
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:56,208
♪ <i>Who knows you treasure
Any simple little pleasure</i> ♪

380
00:34:56,292 --> 00:35:01,375
♪ <i>Like a full-length mink
To cover last year's blouse</i> ♪

381
00:35:01,458 --> 00:35:04,750
♪ <i>It's so nice</i> ♪

382
00:35:04,833 --> 00:35:08,458
♪ <i>To have a man
Around the house...</i> ♪

383
00:35:10,167 --> 00:35:11,625
You're awfully skinny,
aren't you?

384
00:35:11,708 --> 00:35:15,292
♪ <i>It's so nice to have
A man around the house</i> ♪

385
00:35:16,583 --> 00:35:21,833
♪ <i>Oh, so nice to have
A man around the house</i> ♪

386
00:35:22,917 --> 00:35:25,333
♪ <i>Just a guy...</i> ♪

387
00:35:25,417 --> 00:35:26,583
You see?

388
00:35:29,292 --> 00:35:30,875
Like riding a bicycle.

389
00:35:33,792 --> 00:35:35,250
Tricycle.

390
00:35:37,750 --> 00:35:38,833
Family.

391
00:35:40,958 --> 00:35:42,958
It is a bike for children.

392
00:35:44,917 --> 00:35:46,208
Children!

393
00:35:57,917 --> 00:35:59,333
You missed the toilet.

394
00:36:15,500 --> 00:36:16,500
What?

395
00:36:17,958 --> 00:36:19,792
Better than
the carpet, I suppose.

396
00:36:22,958 --> 00:36:25,750
When do you expect your wife
might join you, Mr. Tóth?

397
00:36:28,792 --> 00:36:30,792
There's not room for the both
of you in that storage space.

398
00:36:36,125 --> 00:36:38,042
I wish I knew, Audrey.

399
00:36:47,542 --> 00:36:49,042
Thank you for the dinner.

400
00:36:52,833 --> 00:36:54,792
Attila showed me
magazine pictures.

401
00:36:56,083 --> 00:36:57,708
The projects you did
at your firm.

402
00:37:00,208 --> 00:37:02,542
You're not what I expected
from what I read about you.

403
00:37:05,208 --> 00:37:08,542
I'm not what
I expected either.

404
00:37:13,208 --> 00:37:15,625
You know,
I'm sure you could get a job.

405
00:37:18,958 --> 00:37:20,292
A better job.

406
00:37:22,375 --> 00:37:23,708
At a firm here.

407
00:37:34,583 --> 00:37:35,708
I then...

408
00:37:38,417 --> 00:37:40,667
...would be working
for someone.

409
00:37:44,458 --> 00:37:46,625
It's better than sleeping
in a storage closet.

410
00:37:55,667 --> 00:37:57,458
I'll look for somewhere else
to stay.

411
00:38:05,458 --> 00:38:08,833
Thank you again...
for the dinner.

412
00:38:36,417 --> 00:38:38,375
Bring the boxes.
Don't drop them.

413
00:38:38,458 --> 00:38:39,458
Here, here, here.

414
00:38:41,875 --> 00:38:43,833
The guy is rich,
he's gonna buy more books.

415
00:38:43,917 --> 00:38:46,167
You be respectful.

416
00:38:46,250 --> 00:38:47,458
The guy likes to read.

417
00:38:47,542 --> 00:38:49,708
He can tell us
a bedtime story.

418
00:38:49,792 --> 00:38:52,833
Okay.
Slowly, slowly. Slowly.

419
00:38:55,083 --> 00:38:55,917
Slowly.

420
00:38:56,000 --> 00:38:57,292
Don't scratch the floor.

421
00:39:17,417 --> 00:39:19,000
<i>Yes, the long panels.</i>

422
00:39:19,083 --> 00:39:20,792
<i>The shelves can vary in height</i>

423
00:39:20,875 --> 00:39:22,625
<i>to accommodate
the larger volumes</i>

424
00:39:22,708 --> 00:39:24,750
<i>our client had been stacking
on the floor.</i>

425
00:39:24,833 --> 00:39:26,958
So, 45 degrees.

426
00:39:27,042 --> 00:39:29,667
Three, two, one.

427
00:39:37,125 --> 00:39:40,125
Perfect. It will be beautiful.

428
00:39:49,583 --> 00:39:51,833
That's it.
That's good, that's good.

429
00:39:55,083 --> 00:39:57,875
Left, Gordon, left.
And steady.

430
00:39:59,208 --> 00:40:00,833
Careful now, left.

431
00:40:00,917 --> 00:40:02,792
One steady movement.

432
00:40:02,875 --> 00:40:04,792
Come on, one steady movement.

433
00:40:05,875 --> 00:40:07,250
Slowly.

434
00:40:07,333 --> 00:40:09,125
Slowly, slowly, slowly.

435
00:40:09,208 --> 00:40:10,833
It's too close to the roof!

436
00:40:11,625 --> 00:40:13,250
Hey, hey, hey, hey!

437
00:40:14,750 --> 00:40:15,792
Oh, no!

438
00:40:21,208 --> 00:40:23,542
- I told you to pull!
- I did what I could.

439
00:40:23,625 --> 00:40:26,250
We have a piece of guttering
to replace now as well.

440
00:40:29,833 --> 00:40:32,542
One, two, three.

441
00:40:43,625 --> 00:40:44,875
Yeah.

442
00:40:48,500 --> 00:40:49,500
Okay.

443
00:40:52,208 --> 00:40:53,792
Put it... bring your hand...

444
00:41:07,333 --> 00:41:10,125
It's good.
It's good, it's good.

445
00:41:10,208 --> 00:41:13,167
Dance with me.
Dance with me again.

446
00:42:31,542 --> 00:42:32,708
Attila.

447
00:42:38,917 --> 00:42:40,875
It's a first edition.

448
00:42:40,958 --> 00:42:42,583
They're all first edition.

449
00:42:45,917 --> 00:42:47,875
You're an idiot.

450
00:42:47,958 --> 00:42:49,625
Stop it. Idiot.

451
00:42:56,333 --> 00:42:57,583
What is this?

452
00:42:58,917 --> 00:43:00,083
What is all this?

453
00:43:01,292 --> 00:43:02,875
Who authorized you to come
into my home

454
00:43:02,958 --> 00:43:04,042
and tear everything apart?

455
00:43:04,875 --> 00:43:07,542
- Excuse me. Excuse me, sir.
- Who the hell are you?

456
00:43:09,542 --> 00:43:11,833
This was all
supposed to be a surprise.

457
00:43:11,917 --> 00:43:13,625
Your son Harry told us
not to expect you...

458
00:43:13,708 --> 00:43:15,000
It is a goddamn surprise!

459
00:43:15,083 --> 00:43:16,792
My mother, an ailing woman,

460
00:43:16,875 --> 00:43:18,292
is sitting outside
on the driveway

461
00:43:18,375 --> 00:43:20,167
too frightened to come inside.

462
00:43:20,250 --> 00:43:21,750
We're sorry
to have frightened her.

463
00:43:21,833 --> 00:43:24,417
We brought her here
for some peace and respite,

464
00:43:24,500 --> 00:43:26,583
only to discover
a strange Negro man

465
00:43:26,667 --> 00:43:28,208
roaming around our property.

466
00:43:28,292 --> 00:43:32,125
Your son...
asked us to come here

467
00:43:32,208 --> 00:43:35,208
to redo the study
into a library.

468
00:43:36,958 --> 00:43:38,333
A library?

469
00:43:40,583 --> 00:43:41,708
The room...

470
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:44,292
it's gutted!

471
00:43:45,417 --> 00:43:48,333
Well, we were just putting
everything back in its place.

472
00:43:48,417 --> 00:43:49,750
You've turned
it all inside out.

473
00:43:49,833 --> 00:43:51,292
How do you know
its proper place?

474
00:43:52,042 --> 00:43:53,875
We have taken excellent care

475
00:43:53,958 --> 00:43:56,000
of your belongings,
Mr. Van Buren.

476
00:43:56,083 --> 00:43:58,292
I...
I don't know what to tell you.

477
00:44:00,208 --> 00:44:01,500
Who are you?

478
00:44:02,333 --> 00:44:03,917
László Tóth.

479
00:44:05,208 --> 00:44:08,917
Lás...
László's a licensed architect.

480
00:44:09,000 --> 00:44:10,958
He supervised the renovation

481
00:44:11,042 --> 00:44:13,708
and I've done business
with your son before.

482
00:44:13,792 --> 00:44:17,333
I have a furniture shop
down in Kensington.

483
00:44:17,417 --> 00:44:18,833
Miller and Sons.

484
00:44:18,917 --> 00:44:21,833
Mr. Van Buren, may I show you
around the space?

485
00:44:21,917 --> 00:44:25,000
The... The work lamps are not
doing the work any justice.

486
00:44:25,083 --> 00:44:27,125
Your Negro man is waiting
for you outside the gate.

487
00:44:27,208 --> 00:44:28,750
I suggest you pack your things
and leave.

488
00:44:35,750 --> 00:44:37,125
Mr. Van Buren...

489
00:44:39,667 --> 00:44:41,042
we are finished here.

490
00:44:42,250 --> 00:44:44,875
It's quite all right. Come.

491
00:44:47,667 --> 00:44:50,000
I will confirm this
with my son in the morning.

492
00:44:51,542 --> 00:44:52,917
My mother is sick.

493
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:55,500
She needs to be inside
so she can sleep!

494
00:44:56,458 --> 00:44:58,125
It's quite all right?

495
00:44:59,250 --> 00:45:01,458
This is not all right,
this is my home!

496
00:45:02,375 --> 00:45:03,833
Goddamn you!

497
00:45:41,667 --> 00:45:42,958
Wake up.

498
00:45:45,667 --> 00:45:47,667
That's a hell of a way
to greet the day.

499
00:45:58,833 --> 00:46:00,042
Harry Lee called.

500
00:46:01,792 --> 00:46:03,167
He says he won't pay.

501
00:46:09,667 --> 00:46:12,000
For... For the materials?

502
00:46:15,250 --> 00:46:17,083
He says
we damaged the property

503
00:46:17,167 --> 00:46:19,208
and I'm lucky if he doesn't
take me to court.

504
00:46:27,208 --> 00:46:28,708
Got nothing to say to that?

505
00:46:31,583 --> 00:46:33,208
What are you going
to do about it?

506
00:46:36,333 --> 00:46:37,625
László...

507
00:46:47,333 --> 00:46:49,125
You run
my clients out the door.

508
00:46:53,958 --> 00:46:55,792
You make a pass at my wife.

509
00:46:57,042 --> 00:47:00,042
She told me.
Of course she told me.

510
00:47:01,833 --> 00:47:04,375
Of course she told me.
What do you expect?

511
00:47:05,125 --> 00:47:08,250
Well, what did I expect?

512
00:47:08,333 --> 00:47:09,792
You couldn't keep
your hands to yourself

513
00:47:09,875 --> 00:47:11,208
even when we were kids.

514
00:47:12,208 --> 00:47:13,917
Listen...

515
00:47:15,375 --> 00:47:17,042
I won't tell Erzsi this time.

516
00:47:21,208 --> 00:47:22,792
I know
you've been through a lot.

517
00:47:25,042 --> 00:47:27,208
That's what I told...
told Audrey too.

518
00:47:35,250 --> 00:47:36,667
I'm not going to hurt you.

519
00:47:38,458 --> 00:47:40,083
But I can't help you anymore
either.

520
00:47:42,333 --> 00:47:43,750
You got that?

521
00:48:19,042 --> 00:48:20,917
<i>Good morning, Philadelphia.</i>

522
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:23,833
<i>It is Thursday,
November 7th, 1950.</i>

523
00:48:23,917 --> 00:48:26,667
<i>This could be the first time
since 1930</i>

524
00:48:26,750 --> 00:48:29,167
<i>that the Republican Party
may seize control...</i>

525
00:48:29,250 --> 00:48:30,500
Gordon.

526
00:48:31,500 --> 00:48:32,667
Gordon.

527
00:48:33,833 --> 00:48:35,708
<i>...US and United Nations
forces</i>

528
00:48:35,792 --> 00:48:37,667
<i>have made significant advances</i>

529
00:48:37,750 --> 00:48:39,042
<i>on the Korean peninsula...</i>

530
00:48:43,708 --> 00:48:45,917
Wake up. Gordon.

531
00:48:46,833 --> 00:48:48,917
Come on.

532
00:48:49,792 --> 00:48:51,000
Wake up.

533
00:49:10,208 --> 00:49:11,458
We gotta go.

534
00:49:11,542 --> 00:49:13,708
I let you sleep in.
Time to get up.

535
00:49:22,333 --> 00:49:24,042
Oh. Gordon.

536
00:49:24,125 --> 00:49:27,417
Has Mr. László already gone?
I need to speak with him.

537
00:49:28,583 --> 00:49:29,625
Hold on.

538
00:49:41,208 --> 00:49:42,458
Hey, there.

539
00:49:55,667 --> 00:49:57,042
László?

540
00:50:01,500 --> 00:50:03,542
It is for my injury.

541
00:50:03,625 --> 00:50:05,792
Sister Elizabeth
is asking for you.

542
00:50:09,417 --> 00:50:10,875
I will be right there.

543
00:50:12,125 --> 00:50:15,625
Do me a favor and hold off on
that until we punch the clock.

544
00:50:32,917 --> 00:50:35,250
What did she want
to talk to you about?

545
00:50:35,333 --> 00:50:37,542
She asked
for my participation.

546
00:50:37,625 --> 00:50:39,917
Like what?
They want you to help out?

547
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:41,958
I already help out.

548
00:50:44,042 --> 00:50:47,458
She wants me to attend
the service on Sundays

549
00:50:47,542 --> 00:50:50,125
and collect donations.

550
00:50:50,208 --> 00:50:52,375
And what did you say to her?

551
00:50:55,500 --> 00:50:57,292
I said I would think about it.

552
00:50:58,458 --> 00:50:59,708
That seems fair, no?

553
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:05,833
I go to somewhere else.

554
00:51:10,167 --> 00:51:12,208
Why don't you ask
for a place to stay,

555
00:51:12,292 --> 00:51:14,250
wherever it is that you do go?

556
00:51:17,417 --> 00:51:22,417
I do not permit my people from
home to see me as a beggar.

557
00:51:22,500 --> 00:51:24,208
Never.

558
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:34,083
♪ <i>A rose must remain</i> ♪

559
00:51:34,167 --> 00:51:38,292
♪ <i>With the sun and the rain</i> ♪

560
00:51:38,375 --> 00:51:44,917
♪ <i>Or its lovely promise
Won't come true</i> ♪

561
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:48,333
♪ <i>To each his own</i> ♪

562
00:51:48,417 --> 00:51:52,417
♪ <i>To each his own</i> ♪

563
00:51:52,500 --> 00:51:57,875
♪ <i>And my own is you</i> ♪

564
00:51:57,958 --> 00:52:00,833
♪ <i>What good is a song</i> ♪

565
00:52:00,917 --> 00:52:04,292
♪ <i>if the words don't belong?</i> ♪

566
00:52:04,375 --> 00:52:10,750
♪ <i>And a dream
Must be a dream for two</i> ♪

567
00:52:10,833 --> 00:52:14,042
♪ <i>No good alone</i> ♪

568
00:52:14,125 --> 00:52:18,250
♪ <i>To each his own</i> ♪

569
00:52:18,333 --> 00:52:22,542
♪ <i>For me, there's you</i> ♪

570
00:52:23,667 --> 00:52:27,458
♪ <i>if a flame is to grow</i> ♪

571
00:52:27,542 --> 00:52:30,917
♪ <i>There must be a glow</i> ♪

572
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:35,667
♪ <i>To open each door
There's a key</i> ♪

573
00:52:55,208 --> 00:52:57,333
There's a son
of a bitch here to see you.

574
00:52:57,417 --> 00:52:58,500
Huh.

575
00:53:00,917 --> 00:53:02,583
László Tóth, is that you?

576
00:53:04,042 --> 00:53:05,250
I've been looking for you.

577
00:53:08,208 --> 00:53:10,542
No wonder I couldn't find you,
you've grown a beard.

578
00:53:15,542 --> 00:53:17,792
What can I do for you, sir?

579
00:53:17,875 --> 00:53:19,708
I would like
to take you to lunch.

580
00:53:22,333 --> 00:53:24,625
We do not break
for another two hours.

581
00:53:25,500 --> 00:53:28,042
Point out your manager.
Let me educate him.

582
00:53:29,375 --> 00:53:30,583
Have you seen that?

583
00:53:34,500 --> 00:53:36,083
I can assure you
everyone else has.

584
00:53:37,125 --> 00:53:38,583
Flip to page 66.

585
00:53:49,042 --> 00:53:50,083
Where did you study?

586
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:54,458
Bauhaus in Dessau.

587
00:53:55,125 --> 00:53:57,667
Bauhaus? How marvelous.

588
00:53:59,417 --> 00:54:01,792
Uh, read the caption
below the photograph.

589
00:54:08,375 --> 00:54:09,250
So what do you think?

590
00:54:11,500 --> 00:54:13,083
Looks good.

591
00:54:13,167 --> 00:54:14,167
Damn right it does.

592
00:54:16,208 --> 00:54:17,625
Why didn't you defend yourself

593
00:54:17,708 --> 00:54:20,375
when I came after you all
like a bat out of hell?

594
00:54:21,708 --> 00:54:24,333
I called that American cousin
of yours, um...

595
00:54:24,417 --> 00:54:26,750
- Attila.
- Yes. Yeah, that's right.

596
00:54:26,833 --> 00:54:29,333
First, I apologized,
then I lauded him with praise.

597
00:54:29,417 --> 00:54:33,375
However, he, quite honorably,
redirected me to you.

598
00:54:34,958 --> 00:54:36,625
And I have since
done my homework.

599
00:54:41,042 --> 00:54:42,875
These are yours, yes?

600
00:54:56,958 --> 00:54:58,458
Yes.

601
00:54:58,542 --> 00:54:59,542
All of them?

602
00:55:06,375 --> 00:55:07,625
Yes.

603
00:55:08,625 --> 00:55:11,125
I'm sorry.
Have... Have I upset you?

604
00:55:12,250 --> 00:55:13,208
No.

605
00:55:15,083 --> 00:55:16,083
Not at all.

606
00:55:20,333 --> 00:55:23,792
I did not realize these images
were still available.

607
00:55:24,583 --> 00:55:26,125
Much less of any consequence.

608
00:55:28,125 --> 00:55:29,917
May I keep these?

609
00:55:30,833 --> 00:55:32,042
Of course you may.

610
00:55:33,417 --> 00:55:34,750
They're very artistic.

611
00:55:38,167 --> 00:55:40,042
They're better
in real life.

612
00:55:41,708 --> 00:55:43,083
You could've elaborated
a little more

613
00:55:43,167 --> 00:55:44,167
on your background.

614
00:55:44,250 --> 00:55:45,333
You didn't...

615
00:55:45,417 --> 00:55:47,208
You didn't do yourself
any favors back there.

616
00:55:48,917 --> 00:55:51,708
It was difficult to interject
amidst all of the shouting.

617
00:55:51,792 --> 00:55:54,625
Yeah.

618
00:55:55,375 --> 00:55:57,167
Yeah, I... I'm ashamed.

619
00:55:59,500 --> 00:56:01,417
Really, I am, I...

620
00:56:01,500 --> 00:56:03,083
I acted a fool.

621
00:56:04,250 --> 00:56:05,583
My...

622
00:56:06,708 --> 00:56:09,250
My mother was dying.

623
00:56:09,333 --> 00:56:10,833
It's not an excuse, but she...

624
00:56:10,917 --> 00:56:13,458
she died that very weekend
at the house.

625
00:56:13,542 --> 00:56:16,458
I'm very sorry
to hear about your mother.

626
00:56:17,583 --> 00:56:19,708
Tell me,
why is an accomplished

627
00:56:19,792 --> 00:56:21,500
foreign architect

628
00:56:21,583 --> 00:56:23,667
shoveling coal
here in Philadelphia?

629
00:56:25,167 --> 00:56:29,542
Well, I'm also
doing the construction

630
00:56:29,625 --> 00:56:30,792
for a bowling alley.

631
00:56:33,792 --> 00:56:35,167
But, um...

632
00:56:41,583 --> 00:56:45,208
The Reich rejected myself
and my colleagues

633
00:56:45,292 --> 00:56:46,792
for our type of work.

634
00:56:48,000 --> 00:56:50,583
For it was deemed
not Germanic in character.

635
00:56:55,083 --> 00:56:57,083
Uh, I don't wish to be rude,

636
00:56:57,167 --> 00:56:59,292
but I only have time
for the coffee.

637
00:57:01,417 --> 00:57:04,000
You were not prepared
for what you saw.

638
00:57:04,083 --> 00:57:05,625
That is understandable.

639
00:57:08,042 --> 00:57:10,708
I'm glad you have come
to appreciate it.

640
00:57:12,042 --> 00:57:14,042
I don't just appreciate it,
Mr. Tóth.

641
00:57:15,125 --> 00:57:16,125
I cherish it.

642
00:57:18,750 --> 00:57:19,958
I hate surprises.

643
00:57:21,083 --> 00:57:23,333
My fat-headed son
should have known better.

644
00:57:23,417 --> 00:57:25,917
But listen, I'm not here
to boast or to grieve.

645
00:57:27,208 --> 00:57:29,083
I've come to pay you
the monies you're owed.

646
00:57:31,833 --> 00:57:34,417
For what it's worth,
it was not my suggestion

647
00:57:34,500 --> 00:57:36,292
you and your partner
should not be paid.

648
00:57:36,375 --> 00:57:38,375
I only found out about that
after the fact.

649
00:57:39,250 --> 00:57:42,583
We damaged some guttering
which we intended to replace,

650
00:57:42,667 --> 00:57:44,458
but it was a misunderstanding.

651
00:57:44,542 --> 00:57:46,042
Forget it. Take the money.

652
00:57:49,792 --> 00:57:51,042
Thank you.

653
00:57:54,167 --> 00:57:56,875
I'd stash that in your
undergarments, if I were you,

654
00:57:56,958 --> 00:57:58,250
or inside of a shoe.

655
00:58:00,500 --> 00:58:02,958
I would like you to come
and see it in the daylight.

656
00:58:05,167 --> 00:58:06,625
I've already seen it.

657
00:58:08,250 --> 00:58:10,083
I'd like you to come
and enjoy it, rather.

658
00:58:12,333 --> 00:58:14,208
- All right.
- Wonderful.

659
00:58:14,917 --> 00:58:16,917
I can have a car come
and pick you up Sunday morning

660
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:18,958
if you're...
if you're not too busy.

661
00:58:20,042 --> 00:58:21,042
No.

662
00:58:22,042 --> 00:58:25,083
Here.
Write me down your address.

663
00:58:39,083 --> 00:58:41,792
I've found our conversation
persuasive

664
00:58:41,875 --> 00:58:44,417
and intellectually
stimulating.

665
00:58:46,208 --> 00:58:47,333
Bye.

666
00:58:48,333 --> 00:58:49,625
It was a pleasure.

667
00:59:54,750 --> 00:59:56,333
Hey, hey, don't move too much.

668
01:00:01,917 --> 01:00:03,875
Going to be some minutes!

669
01:00:03,958 --> 01:00:05,458
One second. Hold this.

670
01:00:54,792 --> 01:00:55,875
Yes, he inside.

671
01:00:55,958 --> 01:00:57,875
Everybody left.
It's time to go. We're closed.

672
01:00:57,958 --> 01:00:59,792
Don't push!
I know he is in there.

673
01:00:59,875 --> 01:01:00,875
Ain't nobody in there.

674
01:01:00,958 --> 01:01:02,750
My friend would not leave me!
Please.

675
01:01:02,833 --> 01:01:04,375
Ain't nobody in there!
It's time to go.

676
01:01:04,458 --> 01:01:06,083
- No! No.
- We're closed.

677
01:01:06,167 --> 01:01:07,708
Now go on home.

678
01:01:08,542 --> 01:01:10,917
Listen, my friend is in there,
please!

679
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:13,875
- Oh! My nose!
- I said go home.

680
01:02:11,583 --> 01:02:12,917
Hey, mister,
the picture's over.

681
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:14,000
You can't sleep here.

682
01:02:14,083 --> 01:02:15,208
<i>Big demand is for these</i>

683
01:02:15,292 --> 01:02:16,542
<i>derivatives of opium,</i>

684
01:02:16,625 --> 01:02:18,250
<i>the narcotic drugs...</i>

685
01:02:18,333 --> 01:02:19,375
<i>...useful in medicine</i>

686
01:02:19,458 --> 01:02:21,958
<i>to relieve pain
and to induce sleep.</i>

687
01:02:22,042 --> 01:02:23,708
<i>Used without supervision,</i>

688
01:02:23,792 --> 01:02:27,375
<i>they can become dangerous,
habit-forming drugs.</i>

689
01:02:27,458 --> 01:02:30,000
<i>Once the habit is formed,
the addict...</i>

690
01:02:32,250 --> 01:02:33,917
<i>...must have a continual
supply at all costs.</i>

691
01:02:34,000 --> 01:02:35,000
Hmm?

692
01:02:35,083 --> 01:02:36,542
<i>Lawfully imported drugs
are not available to him.</i>

693
01:02:36,625 --> 01:02:38,250
<i>He must turn
to an illegal source.</i>

694
01:02:38,333 --> 01:02:39,500
Come.

695
01:02:40,583 --> 01:02:41,833
Come with me.

696
01:02:41,917 --> 01:02:44,375
Good kitty. Come with me.

697
01:02:45,500 --> 01:02:47,875
- Just come.
- Excuse me, Mr. Tóth.

698
01:02:49,542 --> 01:02:51,833
The Van Buren family
sent me for you.

699
01:03:04,042 --> 01:03:05,542
On the seat there beside you,

700
01:03:05,625 --> 01:03:07,083
there's a pressed
dinner jacket.

701
01:03:27,625 --> 01:03:30,500
Ah. There you are!

702
01:03:33,542 --> 01:03:34,708
Man of the hour.

703
01:03:36,625 --> 01:03:37,917
What have you
done to yourself?

704
01:03:38,958 --> 01:03:40,375
Fell off a beam and...

705
01:03:40,458 --> 01:03:41,542
Everyone's famished.

706
01:03:41,625 --> 01:03:42,875
Harry,
you remember each other.

707
01:03:43,708 --> 01:03:46,458
Yes, I do. Afternoon.

708
01:03:46,542 --> 01:03:48,542
Daddy, the kitchen's asking

709
01:03:48,625 --> 01:03:49,833
if we could
please take our seats.

710
01:03:49,917 --> 01:03:51,708
And this is Harry's
twin sister, Maggie.

711
01:03:52,417 --> 01:03:55,250
Hello, Mr. Tóth.
We love the library.

712
01:03:55,333 --> 01:03:56,750
Thank you.

713
01:03:56,833 --> 01:03:58,167
All right, let's eat.

714
01:03:58,250 --> 01:04:01,000
He won't tout his own
accomplishments, but...

715
01:04:01,083 --> 01:04:02,875
Mr. Tóth's work is celebrated

716
01:04:02,958 --> 01:04:05,625
throughout much of Western
and Central Europe.

717
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:11,083
There are many features on him
in architectural journals,

718
01:04:11,167 --> 01:04:12,792
if you follow
that sort of thing.

719
01:04:13,667 --> 01:04:15,292
What was your focus?

720
01:04:20,458 --> 01:04:25,917
Uh, theaters, synagogues,
restorations.

721
01:04:27,375 --> 01:04:30,667
Many projects
but some quite unusual.

722
01:04:31,583 --> 01:04:33,500
Are you married, Mr. Tóth?

723
01:04:36,167 --> 01:04:37,208
Yes.

724
01:04:40,500 --> 01:04:41,750
She's still in Europe.

725
01:04:43,000 --> 01:04:44,167
Why's that?

726
01:04:47,750 --> 01:04:48,875
We were separated.

727
01:04:50,750 --> 01:04:51,708
Forcibly.

728
01:04:54,958 --> 01:04:58,083
Where is it you come from,
if you don't mind my asking?

729
01:04:58,167 --> 01:05:00,375
I... I can't place the accent.

730
01:05:00,458 --> 01:05:01,750
The city of Budapest.

731
01:05:03,333 --> 01:05:04,625
Stop it.

732
01:05:04,708 --> 01:05:08,417
Ravaged during the war.
Just terrible.

733
01:05:09,500 --> 01:05:10,750
What was it like, the war?

734
01:05:12,000 --> 01:05:14,750
We hear some stories here
that make one's toes curl.

735
01:05:18,792 --> 01:05:20,083
I would not know

736
01:05:20,167 --> 01:05:21,750
where to begin, Mrs. Hoffman.

737
01:05:24,000 --> 01:05:26,208
Do you plan on
returning to Europe, Mr. Tóth?

738
01:05:33,917 --> 01:05:38,417
But my wife, she tries to come
now, here, to join me.

739
01:05:40,042 --> 01:05:41,958
But the situation
is difficult.

740
01:05:42,792 --> 01:05:44,667
Well,
with Roosevelt gone now,

741
01:05:44,750 --> 01:05:45,750
that should
make things easier.

742
01:05:47,208 --> 01:05:49,333
He is gone, but...

743
01:05:49,417 --> 01:05:51,250
everyone is still frightened

744
01:05:51,333 --> 01:05:52,583
that people like me

745
01:05:52,667 --> 01:05:55,250
are a threat
to their national defense.

746
01:05:58,042 --> 01:06:01,708
When you say "people,"
you mean Jews?

747
01:06:04,458 --> 01:06:05,708
We're Jewish.

748
01:06:07,833 --> 01:06:09,208
Michelle converted.

749
01:06:12,458 --> 01:06:13,750
Mm.

750
01:06:16,333 --> 01:06:17,708
As did my Erzsébet.

751
01:06:19,333 --> 01:06:22,667
It required a great
deal of commitment and study,

752
01:06:22,750 --> 01:06:25,167
but...

753
01:06:25,250 --> 01:06:27,167
...few at home
recognized her for it.

754
01:06:28,083 --> 01:06:32,208
A pity the National Socialists
could not see it their way.

755
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:36,625
But no, not only Jewish.

756
01:06:36,708 --> 01:06:38,708
Foreign people.

757
01:06:40,333 --> 01:06:44,292
I was fortunate to depart
from Bremerhaven when I did.

758
01:06:46,333 --> 01:06:50,542
Truman's order facilitated
the transfer of my group.

759
01:06:52,792 --> 01:06:54,417
Others were not so lucky.

760
01:06:57,167 --> 01:06:59,167
That sounds
very painful, László.

761
01:07:00,333 --> 01:07:02,208
We're terribly sorry for you.

762
01:07:04,083 --> 01:07:06,708
Michael is my friend
and my attorney,

763
01:07:06,792 --> 01:07:08,125
in that order.

764
01:07:09,042 --> 01:07:10,292
Michael, is this a process

765
01:07:10,375 --> 01:07:12,208
your firm
could help to expedite?

766
01:07:12,792 --> 01:07:15,750
It is not so simple,
I'm afraid.

767
01:07:18,500 --> 01:07:23,417
My wife cannot leave my niece
behind because she is...

768
01:07:25,250 --> 01:07:28,542
young, motherless,
and is very sick.

769
01:07:30,167 --> 01:07:31,583
It's just the two of 'em?

770
01:07:34,000 --> 01:07:36,667
I'd be glad to make an enquiry
on your behalf.

771
01:07:38,042 --> 01:07:39,125
You know there's something

772
01:07:39,208 --> 01:07:40,625
called
the Displaced Persons Act

773
01:07:40,708 --> 01:07:42,458
that's recently
gone into effect.

774
01:07:43,667 --> 01:07:46,958
It will allow some
200,000 European persons

775
01:07:47,042 --> 01:07:48,917
admission
for permanent residence.

776
01:07:50,417 --> 01:07:52,042
You can read
about it in the paper now.

777
01:07:53,042 --> 01:07:54,167
Michael's firm represents

778
01:07:54,250 --> 01:07:55,417
the office
of the Vice President.

779
01:07:58,458 --> 01:07:59,583
The President?

780
01:08:00,542 --> 01:08:01,917
Of the United States.

781
01:08:02,000 --> 01:08:04,208
Congratulations.

782
01:08:05,958 --> 01:08:08,875
Come see me in our
Philadelphia office on Monday.

783
01:08:08,958 --> 01:08:13,042
Telephone this line,
and my assistant can arrange.

784
01:08:13,125 --> 01:08:16,292
She'll tell you what we'll
need you both to provide.

785
01:08:19,083 --> 01:08:20,042
Thank you.

786
01:08:22,333 --> 01:08:25,125
I think we'll take
coffee in the study, huh?

787
01:08:30,667 --> 01:08:31,833
Thank you.

788
01:08:37,208 --> 01:08:38,667
I was married once.

789
01:08:40,250 --> 01:08:42,375
She gave me
two beautiful children.

790
01:08:44,125 --> 01:08:47,167
Nevertheless, my mother,
Margaret, and the twins

791
01:08:47,250 --> 01:08:48,375
demanded my attention

792
01:08:48,458 --> 01:08:50,833
every minute
of my scarce personal time.

793
01:08:51,625 --> 01:08:53,292
Things became awkward

794
01:08:53,375 --> 01:08:55,792
between my ex-wife
and Margaret.

795
01:08:55,875 --> 01:08:57,583
So we separated.

796
01:08:57,667 --> 01:08:58,667
Amicably.

797
01:08:59,625 --> 01:09:01,625
Margaret raised me on her own
in Rochester.

798
01:09:01,708 --> 01:09:03,125
It was just the two of us.

799
01:09:04,792 --> 01:09:09,042
Her parents had disowned her
for a child out of wedlock.

800
01:09:11,667 --> 01:09:13,208
She was my only real family,

801
01:09:14,083 --> 01:09:17,417
other than the twins
later on in life, of course.

802
01:09:19,708 --> 01:09:20,708
I'll tell you...

803
01:09:22,125 --> 01:09:23,375
shortly before their death,

804
01:09:24,167 --> 01:09:25,375
my mother's parents,

805
01:09:26,417 --> 01:09:28,833
I hesitate to call them
my grandparents...

806
01:09:30,250 --> 01:09:31,708
they reached out
to Margaret and me

807
01:09:31,792 --> 01:09:32,833
after reading an article

808
01:09:32,917 --> 01:09:35,625
on the reported success
of my first company.

809
01:09:37,125 --> 01:09:38,250
In actual fact...

810
01:09:39,917 --> 01:09:41,542
we weren't doing that well
at the time

811
01:09:41,625 --> 01:09:43,250
and would soon
shutter our doors,

812
01:09:43,333 --> 01:09:45,500
but this was not yet
public knowledge.

813
01:09:50,750 --> 01:09:55,958
I gather you conclude from our
prior interactions I am blunt,

814
01:09:56,042 --> 01:09:59,750
not hyperbolic
or particularly sentimental.

815
01:10:02,667 --> 01:10:04,042
But my mother...

816
01:10:07,042 --> 01:10:09,542
she was defenseless
against their chumminess.

817
01:10:10,750 --> 01:10:12,042
She argued
that they could very well

818
01:10:12,125 --> 01:10:13,542
be sick or dying and...

819
01:10:15,250 --> 01:10:17,208
quite likely needed the money.

820
01:10:18,917 --> 01:10:23,500
I didn't like seeing Margaret,
an ordinarily pragmatic woman,

821
01:10:23,583 --> 01:10:26,042
reduced to such
bromidic assumptions.

822
01:10:26,125 --> 01:10:28,792
Still, I agreed
to meet with them in person,

823
01:10:28,875 --> 01:10:30,458
in part to appease her,

824
01:10:30,542 --> 01:10:34,167
but also to satisfy
the curiosities of my lineage.

825
01:10:35,000 --> 01:10:38,083
Do you know,
it really is very clever.

826
01:10:38,167 --> 01:10:40,750
The way the space
surrounds one,

827
01:10:40,833 --> 01:10:42,250
the forced perspective.

828
01:10:42,333 --> 01:10:43,875
I think so, yes.

829
01:10:43,958 --> 01:10:47,250
It reminds me
of a short story I once read.

830
01:10:47,333 --> 01:10:49,458
It's about
a never-ending library.

831
01:10:49,542 --> 01:10:52,167
Are you working on anything
at the moment, Mr. Tóth?

832
01:10:53,708 --> 01:10:55,375
A bowling alley.

833
01:10:55,458 --> 01:10:57,250
Pardon me,
I was just in the middle

834
01:10:57,333 --> 01:10:58,875
of telling our friend here
a story.

835
01:10:58,958 --> 01:11:02,083
I'm so sorry. Not at all.
Please excuse me.

836
01:11:10,792 --> 01:11:12,583
You agreed to see them.

837
01:11:14,250 --> 01:11:16,208
We exchanged pleasantries

838
01:11:16,292 --> 01:11:18,417
over the telephone and
I offered to meet with them

839
01:11:18,500 --> 01:11:20,000
at their modest
apartment residence

840
01:11:20,083 --> 01:11:22,417
in a neighboring town.

841
01:11:22,500 --> 01:11:23,583
I laughed to realize

842
01:11:23,667 --> 01:11:25,625
they'd been so nearby
all those years.

843
01:11:27,083 --> 01:11:28,250
On the drive over...

844
01:11:30,208 --> 01:11:31,625
I had time to think.

845
01:11:32,583 --> 01:11:34,292
And I finally arrived
at a figure

846
01:11:34,375 --> 01:11:37,250
I felt comfortable
in offering the two of them,

847
01:11:37,333 --> 01:11:40,167
seeing that they were,
whether I liked it or not,

848
01:11:40,250 --> 01:11:42,917
our only living relatives.

849
01:11:43,000 --> 01:11:45,250
I was received hospitably,

850
01:11:45,333 --> 01:11:49,375
so I swiftly moved to explain
I'd made them out a check

851
01:11:49,458 --> 01:11:51,625
for the amount of $25,000.

852
01:11:53,000 --> 01:11:56,125
When I handed it over,
they appeared relieved,

853
01:11:56,208 --> 01:11:58,625
but perhaps a little
disappointed at the figure.

854
01:11:58,708 --> 01:12:01,875
They were courteous
and thanked me all the same.

855
01:12:02,875 --> 01:12:04,625
I was quite uncomfortable.

856
01:12:06,917 --> 01:12:10,792
But before hurrying off,
I asked them a question.

857
01:12:12,333 --> 01:12:14,417
What will you do
with all this money?

858
01:12:17,042 --> 01:12:20,125
They rambled on about miracles
or some such thing.

859
01:12:20,208 --> 01:12:22,333
For a moment, everything
in their immediate

860
01:12:22,417 --> 01:12:25,625
line of view
seemed solvable, achievable.

861
01:12:26,500 --> 01:12:28,125
They would
finally be all right and...

862
01:12:29,208 --> 01:12:31,792
what a thoughtful
grandson I was.

863
01:12:33,375 --> 01:12:34,583
Upon departure...

864
01:12:36,625 --> 01:12:38,833
before I even reached
the edge of their front lawn,

865
01:12:38,917 --> 01:12:41,625
the two of them came running
out after me, shouting.

866
01:12:43,500 --> 01:12:45,500
"You've forgotten
your signature, Harrison."

867
01:12:48,333 --> 01:12:49,958
I summoned the courage
to be frank

868
01:12:50,042 --> 01:12:51,750
and to speak to them
as adults.

869
01:12:51,833 --> 01:12:54,250
I had not forgotten, I said,

870
01:12:54,333 --> 01:12:56,333
but was not ultimately
compelled to sign

871
01:12:56,417 --> 01:12:58,500
due to the blunder
of their response.

872
01:13:03,417 --> 01:13:05,292
They took it as such a shock.

873
01:13:05,375 --> 01:13:07,000
I thought for a moment
it might kill them

874
01:13:07,083 --> 01:13:08,292
right there
on their front lawn.

875
01:13:08,375 --> 01:13:11,542
But the two of them just wept
and came apart like beggars.

876
01:13:11,625 --> 01:13:15,125
The whole thing
was so much more disturbing

877
01:13:15,208 --> 01:13:16,375
than I'd imagined.

878
01:13:19,125 --> 01:13:20,458
And so on condition...

879
01:13:22,542 --> 01:13:24,625
that they let Margaret alone
from then on...

880
01:13:26,125 --> 01:13:27,667
I struck them
a separate check

881
01:13:27,750 --> 01:13:29,500
for $500 and I signed.

882
01:13:32,250 --> 01:13:35,583
That is how much
I loved my mother, Mr. Tóth.

883
01:13:36,875 --> 01:13:38,625
We did things for each other.

884
01:13:39,500 --> 01:13:41,042
What could they expect

885
01:13:41,125 --> 01:13:43,167
after the way
they had treated you both?

886
01:13:43,250 --> 01:13:45,958
Yes, yes,
that's exactly how I see it.

887
01:13:46,042 --> 01:13:47,833
Answer me something.

888
01:13:48,917 --> 01:13:51,083
Why architecture?

889
01:13:54,625 --> 01:13:55,917
Is it a test?

890
01:13:57,917 --> 01:13:59,083
No, it is not.

891
01:14:08,458 --> 01:14:12,417
Nothing
is of its own explanation.

892
01:14:18,750 --> 01:14:21,667
Is there a better description
of a cube

893
01:14:21,750 --> 01:14:24,042
than that of its construction?

894
01:14:27,208 --> 01:14:29,333
There was a war on.

895
01:14:29,417 --> 01:14:30,542
And yet...

896
01:14:31,833 --> 01:14:33,417
it is my understanding that...

897
01:14:35,875 --> 01:14:39,208
many of the sites
of my projects have survived.

898
01:14:40,458 --> 01:14:43,875
They remain there
still in the city.

899
01:14:47,958 --> 01:14:50,042
When the terrible
recollections

900
01:14:50,125 --> 01:14:53,333
of what happened in Europe
cease to humiliate us...

901
01:14:55,083 --> 01:14:57,417
I expect for them to serve

902
01:14:57,500 --> 01:15:00,083
instead as a political
stimulus,

903
01:15:01,208 --> 01:15:04,542
sparking the upheavals
that so frequently occur

904
01:15:04,625 --> 01:15:07,708
in the cycles of people hood.

905
01:15:17,375 --> 01:15:18,917
I already anticipate

906
01:15:19,000 --> 01:15:23,500
a communal rhetoric
of anger and fear.

907
01:15:26,583 --> 01:15:31,667
A whole river of such
frivolities may flow undammed.

908
01:15:37,000 --> 01:15:42,000
But my buildings were devised
to endure such erosion

909
01:15:42,083 --> 01:15:43,875
of the Danube's shoreline.

910
01:15:49,583 --> 01:15:51,542
What a poetic reply.

911
01:15:54,500 --> 01:15:56,667
You must have been
a beloved professor.

912
01:16:00,250 --> 01:16:01,333
I've said it before,

913
01:16:01,417 --> 01:16:03,250
but I find
our conversations...

914
01:16:04,958 --> 01:16:06,917
intellectually stimulating.

915
01:16:08,750 --> 01:16:10,625
I agree with you.

916
01:16:15,042 --> 01:16:17,458
Everyone, please.

917
01:16:18,750 --> 01:16:21,500
Take your brandy
and join me outside.

918
01:16:22,833 --> 01:16:24,333
I have a terrific surprise.

919
01:16:30,375 --> 01:16:32,625
Where the hell
are you taking us, Harrison?

920
01:16:32,708 --> 01:16:33,875
It's freezing out here.

921
01:16:33,958 --> 01:16:35,958
Just try doing
this in heels, Michael.

922
01:16:46,667 --> 01:16:49,333
Only
a little further. Come on.

923
01:16:53,500 --> 01:16:55,333
Bear with us, everyone.

924
01:16:57,667 --> 01:16:59,792
Hold your horses,
we're almost there.

925
01:17:24,708 --> 01:17:25,708
All right.

926
01:17:27,667 --> 01:17:29,333
As many of you know,

927
01:17:29,417 --> 01:17:32,417
this... this past year
has been somewhat difficult

928
01:17:32,500 --> 01:17:34,917
for Harry, Maggie and myself.

929
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:36,417
Daddy,
it's very cold out here.

930
01:17:36,500 --> 01:17:37,917
Shall we go back inside?

931
01:17:38,000 --> 01:17:40,250
Maggie, please. Quiet.

932
01:17:42,500 --> 01:17:45,875
I've brought you all out here
this evening in the cold

933
01:17:45,958 --> 01:17:48,958
not to glance over my shoulder
at the past,

934
01:17:49,042 --> 01:17:54,167
but to join me in looking
forward toward the future.

935
01:17:54,917 --> 01:17:57,417
As you know,
over this rise is Doylestown.

936
01:17:58,250 --> 01:17:59,792
And so on this site,

937
01:18:00,625 --> 01:18:04,083
we plan to build a center
for the community

938
01:18:04,167 --> 01:18:06,750
in the name
of Margaret Lee Van Buren.

939
01:18:07,917 --> 01:18:09,583
Harrison, that's lovely.

940
01:18:10,542 --> 01:18:13,125
This shall be
a sacred enough space

941
01:18:13,208 --> 01:18:16,208
that perhaps her soul
might inhabit it.

942
01:18:16,292 --> 01:18:21,125
A place for gathering,
reflecting, learning.

943
01:18:22,708 --> 01:18:23,750
And, Mr. Tóth...

944
01:18:25,000 --> 01:18:26,458
I would like you
to build this for her.

945
01:18:26,542 --> 01:18:29,125
Something boundless,
something new.

946
01:18:30,417 --> 01:18:32,792
This has shocked you, I see.
I'm delighted.

947
01:18:32,875 --> 01:18:34,208
I thought perhaps
you might see it coming.

948
01:18:35,208 --> 01:18:37,625
No. No.

949
01:18:37,708 --> 01:18:38,792
Listen.

950
01:18:40,000 --> 01:18:43,792
It is no coincidence
that fate brought us together

951
01:18:44,625 --> 01:18:46,208
on the eve
of my mother's death.

952
01:18:48,583 --> 01:18:50,125
I'm good at reading the signs.

953
01:18:51,917 --> 01:18:54,958
Sir, I do not know
what the commission entails.

954
01:18:55,042 --> 01:18:56,542
We'll talk about the details
at home,

955
01:18:56,625 --> 01:18:57,917
but you'll be
well compensated.

956
01:18:58,000 --> 01:18:59,333
And also...

957
01:18:59,417 --> 01:19:01,833
you'll be given a place
here on the property

958
01:19:01,917 --> 01:19:03,042
to live and work.

959
01:19:03,125 --> 01:19:06,333
I think that residing here

960
01:19:06,417 --> 01:19:08,292
will allow you the time
and the space

961
01:19:08,375 --> 01:19:10,042
to conceive of it properly.

962
01:19:10,917 --> 01:19:13,125
And your family,
should they arrive,

963
01:19:14,333 --> 01:19:15,667
they're welcome here too.

964
01:19:17,000 --> 01:19:18,375
What do you say?

965
01:19:20,542 --> 01:19:24,000
Well, I...
I... uh...

966
01:19:25,250 --> 01:19:28,625
I would like to draw something
and then present it to you.

967
01:19:30,625 --> 01:19:32,375
You'd like to win
the commission.

968
01:19:34,083 --> 01:19:35,417
All right, you can do that.

969
01:19:36,542 --> 01:19:38,875
It's cold,
let's return inside.

970
01:19:39,667 --> 01:19:40,833
Come on.

971
01:19:58,625 --> 01:19:59,875
Excuse me.

972
01:20:00,708 --> 01:20:02,417
I am sorry, I am sorry.

973
01:20:02,500 --> 01:20:06,083
A driver brought me here,
I don't recall his name.

974
01:20:06,167 --> 01:20:09,833
- Sorry.
- No, I need to get back. I...

975
01:20:09,917 --> 01:20:12,000
Could someone possibly
contact the man

976
01:20:12,083 --> 01:20:13,958
who dropped me here
this afternoon?

977
01:20:14,042 --> 01:20:15,458
One minute, please.

978
01:20:29,333 --> 01:20:32,583
Mr. Tóth. I'm sorry
to have kept you waiting.

979
01:20:32,667 --> 01:20:35,917
Harrison's gone to bed.
He wishes you a good night.

980
01:20:36,000 --> 01:20:38,167
Would you help me
to find the driver?

981
01:20:38,250 --> 01:20:39,375
Listen...

982
01:20:40,458 --> 01:20:43,292
I'm terribly sorry
about my father's theatrics.

983
01:20:44,167 --> 01:20:45,625
Must have
caught you off guard.

984
01:20:46,708 --> 01:20:48,250
It's quite all right.

985
01:20:48,333 --> 01:20:49,750
He often makes these decisions

986
01:20:49,833 --> 01:20:51,625
without consulting
the rest of us.

987
01:20:53,167 --> 01:20:55,250
I did not take
any of it to heart.

988
01:20:55,333 --> 01:20:56,792
Oh, you should.

989
01:20:57,792 --> 01:20:59,250
Oh, you should, you see.

990
01:21:02,208 --> 01:21:04,708
My father would like us
to hire you.

991
01:21:06,458 --> 01:21:07,458
Oh.

992
01:21:15,208 --> 01:21:17,333
Ah.

993
01:21:19,917 --> 01:21:23,167
I don't have
any infrastructure here.

994
01:21:23,250 --> 01:21:24,417
That's why he's asked me

995
01:21:24,500 --> 01:21:26,542
to oversee and assist you
in this endeavor.

996
01:21:26,625 --> 01:21:29,792
I have no idea
of the parameters.

997
01:21:29,875 --> 01:21:31,417
Once I have distilled

998
01:21:31,500 --> 01:21:35,417
the essence
of Father's outburst,

999
01:21:35,500 --> 01:21:37,917
I'll try and make
some economic sense of it.

1000
01:21:38,958 --> 01:21:40,833
We've quite a full house
this evening,

1001
01:21:40,917 --> 01:21:42,958
so I took the liberty
of making up a place for you

1002
01:21:43,042 --> 01:21:44,250
in the guest house.

1003
01:21:44,333 --> 01:21:46,458
We can have your things
sent for in the morning.

1004
01:22:02,042 --> 01:22:04,000
Mr. Tóth?

1005
01:22:05,333 --> 01:22:07,208
Mr. Tóth?

1006
01:22:27,250 --> 01:22:29,042
One minute.

1007
01:22:32,083 --> 01:22:33,083
Sir?

1008
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:38,375
You rang for me, sir?

1009
01:22:38,458 --> 01:22:41,625
Oh, yes, László, come in.
I've had a vision.

1010
01:22:46,875 --> 01:22:48,750
I have some sketches.

1011
01:22:48,833 --> 01:22:51,792
I... Also something
I have been working on

1012
01:22:51,875 --> 01:22:55,208
which might be applicable
here, if you care to look.

1013
01:22:55,292 --> 01:22:58,458
In a moment,
my eyes are bleary. Sit down.

1014
01:23:02,208 --> 01:23:04,042
Pardon my appearance,
I have...

1015
01:23:04,125 --> 01:23:06,625
I have carpenters
in the forehead

1016
01:23:06,708 --> 01:23:08,375
causing a terrible ringing
in my ears.

1017
01:23:08,458 --> 01:23:10,375
You'll have to bear with me.

1018
01:23:10,458 --> 01:23:11,583
I can come back.

1019
01:23:11,667 --> 01:23:15,542
Shh! Before I lose it.
Dreams slip away.

1020
01:23:16,458 --> 01:23:18,042
Yes, I know.

1021
01:23:21,500 --> 01:23:23,667
Doylestown, it's beautiful,

1022
01:23:23,750 --> 01:23:26,125
but it's not a cultural place,
you know?

1023
01:23:27,583 --> 01:23:30,417
- Sure.
- But it could be.

1024
01:23:31,917 --> 01:23:34,250
If there were an auditorium,

1025
01:23:34,333 --> 01:23:37,167
it could host a...
a theater festival.

1026
01:23:38,458 --> 01:23:39,458
Sure.

1027
01:23:39,542 --> 01:23:40,875
And in the off season,
of course,

1028
01:23:40,958 --> 01:23:44,292
the local students
could access it.

1029
01:23:44,375 --> 01:23:46,042
Yes.

1030
01:23:46,125 --> 01:23:48,292
And what do you think
about a gymnasium?

1031
01:23:48,375 --> 01:23:51,375
I used to practice wrestling
when I was a teenager.

1032
01:23:52,417 --> 01:23:54,500
I have these fond memories
of my mother

1033
