- Isn't it?

1283
01:44:22,125 --> 01:44:23,292
Erzsébet...

1284
01:44:23,375 --> 01:44:26,292
Pardon me, am I pronouncing
that correctly?

1285
01:44:26,375 --> 01:44:29,208
That's fine, just fine.

1286
01:44:29,292 --> 01:44:33,000
Feel free to call me Elizabeth
if you prefer it.

1287
01:44:33,083 --> 01:44:34,875
And your English
is impressive.

1288
01:44:34,958 --> 01:44:38,708
Thank you. I attended
university in England.

1289
01:44:38,792 --> 01:44:40,625
Oh. Where?

1290
01:44:40,708 --> 01:44:43,958
Oxford. To study English.

1291
01:44:44,042 --> 01:44:47,167
And I returned home
for communications.

1292
01:44:47,250 --> 01:44:48,875
And did you do anything
with that?

1293
01:44:48,958 --> 01:44:52,125
Yes. I wrote tor
a popular national paper

1294
01:44:52,208 --> 01:44:54,333
at home, <i>Magyar Nemzet.</i>

1295
01:44:54,417 --> 01:44:56,708
Huh.
A journalist. Hmm!

1296
01:44:56,792 --> 01:44:59,292
- Cultural?
- Foreign affairs.

1297
01:44:59,375 --> 01:45:01,500
Well, perhaps
you can help your husband

1298
01:45:01,583 --> 01:45:04,167
sound less like
he shines shoes for a wage.

1299
01:45:04,250 --> 01:45:06,000
Haven't you told them anything
about me?

1300
01:45:06,083 --> 01:45:09,250
László, how long have you been
here now? Four, five years?

1301
01:45:09,333 --> 01:45:11,333
You have no excuse anymore.

1302
01:45:14,250 --> 01:45:16,125
I'm sorry. I got
a little carried away there.

1303
01:45:16,208 --> 01:45:18,083
Will you please
pass that back?

1304
01:45:33,083 --> 01:45:34,667
A penny saved.

1305
01:45:39,000 --> 01:45:41,000
Sofia, is that right?

1306
01:45:41,833 --> 01:45:43,042
Zsófia.

1307
01:45:43,875 --> 01:45:45,500
Zsófia.

1308
01:45:45,583 --> 01:45:46,917
Zsófia.

1309
01:45:48,750 --> 01:45:50,667
Does she understand English?

1310
01:45:50,750 --> 01:45:51,917
- Yes.
- Yes.

1311
01:45:54,292 --> 01:45:57,292
Yes.
She understands very well.

1312
01:45:58,958 --> 01:46:02,542
The woman
behind the man.

1313
01:46:09,250 --> 01:46:12,042
László? May I have a word?

1314
01:46:16,250 --> 01:46:17,583
Yes, sir?

1315
01:46:17,667 --> 01:46:18,875
On Leslie's recommendation,

1316
01:46:18,958 --> 01:46:20,750
we've shown your plans
to another architect.

1317
01:46:20,833 --> 01:46:23,333
What? Who?

1318
01:46:23,417 --> 01:46:24,583
Just somebody we worked with

1319
01:46:24,667 --> 01:46:26,208
on a department store
downtown.

1320
01:46:26,292 --> 01:46:27,958
These are minor changes.

1321
01:46:28,042 --> 01:46:29,875
Places they thought
we might save a penny.

1322
01:46:30,625 --> 01:46:31,875
László?

1323
01:46:31,958 --> 01:46:34,542
- Leslie is a bastard.
- Yes, he is.

1324
01:46:34,625 --> 01:46:36,375
That's what we pay him for.

1325
01:46:37,750 --> 01:46:40,667
Ladies, delighted
to have you with us.

1326
01:47:15,167 --> 01:47:17,750
Even when she was ill,

1327
01:47:17,833 --> 01:47:19,792
she was so beautiful.

1328
01:47:56,750 --> 01:47:59,083
If you want
to start a row with me,

1329
01:47:59,167 --> 01:48:01,417
I might as well work out
my English.

1330
01:48:01,500 --> 01:48:03,500
Stop it. Your English
is perfectly all right.

1331
01:48:03,583 --> 01:48:05,667
It was an unimaginative joke

1332
01:48:05,750 --> 01:48:08,042
he told about
you shining shoes.

1333
01:48:13,750 --> 01:48:18,083
Tomorrow, I will take you
to see someone.

1334
01:48:19,000 --> 01:48:20,500
A specialist.

1335
01:48:22,542 --> 01:48:24,625
Don't be angry with me.

1336
01:48:30,750 --> 01:48:32,500
Do you not want to be with me
anymore?

1337
01:48:32,583 --> 01:48:34,500
Stop this nonsense.

1338
01:48:36,083 --> 01:48:37,875
Do you think I look older?

1339
01:48:41,792 --> 01:48:43,625
We <i>are</i> older.

1340
01:48:43,708 --> 01:48:46,500
Can't you say
anything kind to me?

1341
01:48:46,583 --> 01:48:48,833
I love you, you cow.

1342
01:49:04,000 --> 01:49:06,292
I don't want to...

1343
01:49:07,083 --> 01:49:09,958
I don't want to hurt you,
physically.

1344
01:49:12,708 --> 01:49:14,292
You won't.

1345
01:49:17,500 --> 01:49:19,500
I had dreams.

1346
01:49:21,875 --> 01:49:25,083
Every night,
I dreamt I was with you.

1347
01:49:27,583 --> 01:49:29,958
I know what you've done,
László.

1348
01:49:31,625 --> 01:49:33,208
And it's all right.

1349
01:49:34,167 --> 01:49:35,958
What are you talking about?

1350
01:49:39,750 --> 01:49:41,417
I know.

1351
01:49:42,000 --> 01:49:44,208
I know.

1352
01:49:44,292 --> 01:49:47,542
- I can't do it.
- I know everything.

1353
01:49:47,625 --> 01:49:49,750
I don't want to do it
right now.

1354
01:49:49,833 --> 01:49:51,208
You see...

1355
01:49:53,333 --> 01:49:55,167
I became sick.

1356
01:49:56,292 --> 01:49:58,292
Very sick.

1357
01:49:59,250 --> 01:50:01,167
I could hardly breathe.

1358
01:50:02,542 --> 01:50:07,167
I yearned to be with you
and it made me sick.

1359
01:50:09,208 --> 01:50:10,958
I nearly died.

1360
01:50:12,500 --> 01:50:16,292
Between life and death,

1361
01:50:17,375 --> 01:50:20,833
I began having fantasies
about you.

1362
01:50:21,958 --> 01:50:23,792
But I realized...

1363
01:50:24,917 --> 01:50:31,125
they were not fantasies
at all, but visions.

1364
01:50:34,750 --> 01:50:36,625
I was with you.

1365
01:50:41,417 --> 01:50:45,542
All the time...
...I was with you.

1366
01:50:47,333 --> 01:50:52,208
My László,
I know what you've done.

1367
01:50:53,000 --> 01:50:54,792
I'm not jealous

1368
01:50:55,875 --> 01:50:59,792
because I was with you
all the time.

1369
01:51:03,833 --> 01:51:08,375
I know everything
that has happened to you.

1370
01:51:10,208 --> 01:51:12,458
And I am here now,

1371
01:51:13,375 --> 01:51:17,417
and I will never leave you.

1372
01:51:24,500 --> 01:51:26,542
My love...

1373
01:51:26,625 --> 01:51:29,875
My love, I cannot bear it
anymore!

1374
01:51:29,958 --> 01:51:33,458
- I cannot bear it.
- You can.

1375
01:51:34,583 --> 01:51:36,167
You can.

1376
01:51:40,125 --> 01:51:42,208
We have a new life.

1377
01:51:43,083 --> 01:51:45,167
A new language.

1378
01:51:49,375 --> 01:51:51,625
We can start again.

1379
01:52:15,208 --> 01:52:16,875
Houp-la!

1380
01:52:16,958 --> 01:52:19,500
Pardon.
Pardon.

1381
01:52:19,583 --> 01:52:22,542
Maggie Lee
lent me some hair color.

1382
01:52:22,625 --> 01:52:24,792
That is wonderful, dear.

1383
01:52:26,667 --> 01:52:29,000
László, are you there?

1384
01:52:29,083 --> 01:52:30,875
Yes, my love.

1385
01:52:30,958 --> 01:52:33,208
The model is beautiful,
darling.

1386
01:52:35,333 --> 01:52:36,875
So beautiful.

1387
01:52:38,625 --> 01:52:39,625
Thank you.

1388
01:52:39,708 --> 01:52:41,125
We're going
into town this afternoon

1389
01:52:41,208 --> 01:52:42,583
to see Attila.

1390
01:52:42,667 --> 01:52:44,250
Would you like to come?

1391
01:52:46,167 --> 01:52:48,750
I have something
this afternoon.

1392
01:52:50,000 --> 01:52:51,333
I cannot.

1393
01:52:55,750 --> 01:52:57,417
I've missed him.

1394
01:53:03,125 --> 01:53:07,625
Just hearing him mill about
in the other room...

1395
01:53:11,042 --> 01:53:13,000
It's fantastic.

1396
01:53:28,833 --> 01:53:29,958
Perhaps we should see

1397
01:53:30,042 --> 01:53:32,917
about some language classes
this afternoon.

1398
01:53:33,000 --> 01:53:36,125
You could take the bus in
on your own.

1399
01:53:36,208 --> 01:53:39,292
I'm positive it is the last
place you would like to be,

1400
01:53:39,375 --> 01:53:41,917
but it will be good for you,

1401
01:53:42,000 --> 01:53:45,125
and I can brief the instructor
or whomever

1402
01:53:45,208 --> 01:53:47,375
about your situation.

1403
01:53:47,458 --> 01:53:50,917
Listening to me babble on
will only get you so far.

1404
01:53:57,292 --> 01:53:58,833
Where are you ladies off to?

1405
01:53:59,375 --> 01:54:01,083
We're going into town.

1406
01:54:01,167 --> 01:54:03,292
Which town?
We have several nearby.

1407
01:54:03,375 --> 01:54:05,833
Philadelphia. To visit family.

1408
01:54:05,917 --> 01:54:07,625
Ah, the American cousin,
of course.

1409
01:54:07,708 --> 01:54:10,500
- So the city, then?
- Yes, yes, the city.

1410
01:54:10,583 --> 01:54:14,583
Ah. Us as well.
Well, don't just stand there.

1411
01:54:14,667 --> 01:54:16,458
Let us give you
and your auntie a lift.

1412
01:54:17,417 --> 01:54:18,708
Thank you.

1413
01:54:21,583 --> 01:54:23,958
I have a friend
in New York, a newspaper man.

1414
01:54:24,042 --> 01:54:25,917
He's always on the lookout
for new talent.

1415
01:54:26,000 --> 01:54:27,542
Should I mention you to him?

1416
01:54:27,625 --> 01:54:29,542
It's very kind
of you, Mr. Van Buren.

1417
01:54:31,792 --> 01:54:33,958
Would that mean I would
have to work out of New York?

1418
01:54:34,042 --> 01:54:36,000
Well, perhaps,
in the beginning.

1419
01:54:36,083 --> 01:54:37,292
But you don't have
the job yet,

1420
01:54:37,375 --> 01:54:38,917
so let's not get ahead
of ourselves.

1421
01:54:39,000 --> 01:54:40,333
Of course not.

1422
01:54:40,417 --> 01:54:42,042
I did not mean it
to be presumptuous.

1423
01:54:42,125 --> 01:54:43,542
No, no.

1424
01:54:45,417 --> 01:54:46,417
In any event,

1425
01:54:46,500 --> 01:54:48,625
you could always commute there
with me at the start.

1426
01:54:48,708 --> 01:54:50,667
I'm there Monday to Friday.

1427
01:54:51,542 --> 01:54:53,625
Yes, that could be fine.

1428
01:54:54,458 --> 01:54:56,167
I would have to speak
with László, though.

1429
01:54:56,250 --> 01:54:57,958
I can assure you,
when ground breaks,

1430
01:54:58,042 --> 01:54:59,917
he will have his hands full.

1431
01:55:00,000 --> 01:55:01,917
And besides, I...

1432
01:55:02,000 --> 01:55:04,708
I enjoy showing friends
around Manhattan.

1433
01:55:04,792 --> 01:55:06,708
You can't have seen much of it
on your way here.

1434
01:55:06,792 --> 01:55:09,167
Penn Station Terminal
was very nice.

1435
01:55:09,250 --> 01:55:11,083
It <i>is</i> very nice.

1436
01:55:11,167 --> 01:55:13,125
It's a pity it's so full
of tramps these days

1437
01:55:13,208 --> 01:55:15,583
hassling women and children
with their arms outstretched.

1438
01:55:15,667 --> 01:55:17,417
They line up and extend
from the walls

1439
01:55:17,500 --> 01:55:19,417
as if integral
to its very foundation

1440
01:55:19,500 --> 01:55:21,000
like some haunted wall mural.

1441
01:55:21,083 --> 01:55:23,667
Perhaps that is why
I felt so at home.

1442
01:55:23,750 --> 01:55:25,917
I'm a former bag lady myself,

1443
01:55:26,500 --> 01:55:30,542
who does also enjoy the work
of the Dutch masters.

1444
01:55:31,792 --> 01:55:33,583
<i>Earthly Delights.</i>

1445
01:55:33,667 --> 01:55:35,667
You heard it
just as I intended.

1446
01:55:35,750 --> 01:55:37,458
Very clever.

1447
01:55:37,542 --> 01:55:40,167
But "integral
to its foundation..."

1448
01:55:41,292 --> 01:55:42,333
A mural is decorative.

1449
01:55:42,417 --> 01:55:44,458
It has nothing to do
with the foundation.

1450
01:55:45,375 --> 01:55:46,708
<i>Touché.</i>

1451
01:55:47,708 --> 01:55:50,042
Where did you get your passion
for architecture?

1452
01:55:50,125 --> 01:55:51,917
Oh,
we've done buildings before,

1453
01:55:52,000 --> 01:55:54,125
but I'd hardly
call them artistic.

1454
01:55:54,208 --> 01:55:57,625
I don't know. Perhaps it was
because my cellar was full.

1455
01:55:58,583 --> 01:56:00,125
Pardon?

1456
01:56:00,208 --> 01:56:02,458
I collect books,
butterflies and such,

1457
01:56:02,542 --> 01:56:05,833
but above all else,
Portuguese Madeira.

1458
01:56:05,917 --> 01:56:08,250
I take it every evening
after supper.

1459
01:56:08,333 --> 01:56:10,583
I've done the math, and if
I were to uncork a bottle

1460
01:56:10,667 --> 01:56:12,542
seven days a week
for the next 30 years,

1461
01:56:12,625 --> 01:56:15,125
the maximum
of my life's expectancy,

1462
01:56:15,208 --> 01:56:18,042
I would need no more
than 10,000 bottles, all told.

1463
01:56:18,125 --> 01:56:19,625
So once the cellar was full,

1464
01:56:19,708 --> 01:56:22,458
it was time to set about
in a new direction.

1465
01:56:22,542 --> 01:56:24,667
Out of the cellar
and into the sky.

1466
01:56:25,417 --> 01:56:28,208
If you were to drink a bottle
of Madeira every day,

1467
01:56:28,292 --> 01:56:30,167
I shouldn't think
you'd last 30 years.

1468
01:56:32,208 --> 01:56:33,750
I always keep good company.

1469
01:56:34,750 --> 01:56:36,167
That helps.

1470
01:56:41,292 --> 01:56:44,042
<i>I wanna be honest and
I want you to be honest too,</i>

1471
01:56:44,125 --> 01:56:45,458
<i>then when we get married...</i>

1472
01:56:45,542 --> 01:56:47,750
Whatever you need.
I'm very grateful.

1473
01:56:47,833 --> 01:56:49,167
Yep, thank you. Yep.

1474
01:56:50,167 --> 01:56:51,792
I'm gonna
have to call you back.

1475
01:56:52,833 --> 01:56:54,333
How dare you?

1476
01:56:54,417 --> 01:56:55,792
How dare I what?

1477
01:56:55,875 --> 01:56:57,792
You go behind the back!

1478
01:56:58,625 --> 01:57:01,500
You have the meeting
with another goddamn designer!

1479
01:57:02,292 --> 01:57:05,333
Who in the hell is James
T. Simpson? Who is he?

1480
01:57:05,417 --> 01:57:07,292
You want to try
to get me sacked!

1481
01:57:07,375 --> 01:57:10,167
I didn't tell him to meet with
anyone. Of course I didn't.

1482
01:57:10,250 --> 01:57:12,875
You think I feel like working
with you hating my guts

1483
01:57:12,958 --> 01:57:15,708
for the next
two godforsaken years?

1484
01:57:17,125 --> 01:57:20,375
Look, Jim Simpson
is a smart guy.

1485
01:57:20,458 --> 01:57:22,042
He doesn't want to
interfere at all.

1486
01:57:22,125 --> 01:57:24,583
I am not approving
these changes.

1487
01:57:24,667 --> 01:57:26,250
Well, I'm afraid
it's not up to you.

1488
01:57:26,333 --> 01:57:27,750
The casts
are already finished.

1489
01:57:27,833 --> 01:57:29,167
We put in that order
over a month ago.

1490
01:57:29,250 --> 01:57:30,250
What?

1491
01:57:30,333 --> 01:57:31,625
This is the first time
you're hearing about it?

1492
01:57:33,167 --> 01:57:35,208
No one tells me
a goddamn thing here!

1493
01:57:35,292 --> 01:57:37,833
Harrison said he would
talk it over with you.

1494
01:57:37,917 --> 01:57:40,792
I'm sorry you found out
this way, I really am.

1495
01:57:43,958 --> 01:57:46,875
There. It is mine again.

1496
01:57:46,958 --> 01:57:49,417
He cuts three meters
from the top,

1497
01:57:49,500 --> 01:57:51,292
I add it to the bottom.

1498
01:57:52,042 --> 01:57:53,250
There you go.

1499
01:57:54,125 --> 01:57:55,583
We can't afford all this.

1500
01:57:55,667 --> 01:57:57,542
I'm already over budget
this quarter.

1501
01:57:57,625 --> 01:57:59,958
You take what you need
from my fee, Leslie.

1502
01:58:00,042 --> 01:58:01,542
Come on, what's the difference

1503
01:58:01,625 --> 01:58:03,167
between 40 and 50 feet,
anyway?

1504
01:58:03,250 --> 01:58:05,083
The ceilings
are still plenty high.

1505
01:58:05,875 --> 01:58:07,542
Get it approved!

1506
01:58:07,625 --> 01:58:09,833
Well, we have a walk-through
next week

1507
01:58:09,917 --> 01:58:11,958
and Jim is supposed
to be there.

1508
01:58:12,042 --> 01:58:13,292
Just hear him out!

1509
01:58:14,042 --> 01:58:17,167
You can state your case
to Harrison and Harry Lee.

1510
01:58:17,250 --> 01:58:18,958
I won't open my mouth,
I swear it.

1511
01:58:19,042 --> 01:58:21,375
Stop talking
and get it approved, Leslie!

1512
01:58:21,458 --> 01:58:23,042
For the cantilevered floors,

1513
01:58:23,125 --> 01:58:25,750
we plan to use upside-down
T-shaped beams

1514
01:58:25,833 --> 01:58:29,000
integrated into concrete slabs
down here.

1515
01:58:29,083 --> 01:58:32,792
This will serve both as the
ceiling for the space above

1516
01:58:32,875 --> 01:58:35,458
and provide resistance
against compression.

1517
01:58:35,542 --> 01:58:38,083
Well, which corridor
are we in now?

1518
01:58:38,167 --> 01:58:40,250
Uh, we're below ground here.

1519
01:58:40,333 --> 01:58:43,375
It's a sort of passageway
between the main unit

1520
01:58:43,458 --> 01:58:45,583
and the three mid-sized
modular units

1521
01:58:45,667 --> 01:58:47,167
to the south and southeast.

1522
01:58:47,250 --> 01:58:49,958
I'm sorry, but I don't see how
any of this acknowledges

1523
01:58:50,042 --> 01:58:51,417
my proposed cuts.

1524
01:58:51,500 --> 01:58:53,458
I took ten feet off the height
of these damn things

1525
01:58:53,542 --> 01:58:55,333
and now we are 30 feet
underground.

1526
01:58:55,417 --> 01:58:57,458
You have added a quarter-mile
or so of tunnel!

1527
01:58:57,542 --> 01:59:01,250
We excavate the entire
diameter of the tunnel system

1528
01:59:01,333 --> 01:59:03,125
- using a full-face method.
- A what?

1529
01:59:03,208 --> 01:59:06,583
So that there is something
inside

1530
01:59:06,667 --> 01:59:09,167
for the people to discover.

1531
01:59:09,917 --> 01:59:13,333
And so that it is
one building, not four!

1532
01:59:15,000 --> 01:59:16,542
For its harmony.

1533
01:59:18,208 --> 01:59:20,500
You said it yourself,
Mr. Van Buren,

1534
01:59:20,583 --> 01:59:22,792
you expected it
to be one building.

1535
01:59:22,875 --> 01:59:24,417
Well, now it is.

1536
01:59:24,500 --> 01:59:26,208
I'm sorry, but we are not
going back inside

1537
01:59:26,292 --> 01:59:28,167
until you look us all
straight in the eye

1538
01:59:28,250 --> 01:59:30,667
and you tell us where
you are willing to compromise.

1539
01:59:30,750 --> 01:59:33,375
Jim, please, tell us again

1540
01:59:33,458 --> 01:59:35,458
what it is
that you have built.

1541
01:59:36,625 --> 01:59:37,625
Tell us.

1542
01:59:37,708 --> 01:59:39,208
I'll tell you what I've built.

1543
01:59:39,292 --> 01:59:42,250
I've built a shopping center
in New Hope,

1544
01:59:42,333 --> 01:59:44,000
a hotel in Stamford,
Connecticut...

1545
01:59:44,083 --> 01:59:46,667
Now, Jim,
let me remind everyone

1546
01:59:46,750 --> 01:59:49,875
that László has offered to
personally offset these costs.

1547
01:59:49,958 --> 01:59:51,667
No, I'm sorry, but you have
asked me to come here

1548
01:59:51,750 --> 01:59:53,458
to tell you what it is
that we do not need.

1549
01:59:53,542 --> 01:59:54,542
Plain and simple,

1550
01:59:54,625 --> 01:59:56,500
the one thing we do not need
is this guy.

1551
01:59:56,583 --> 01:59:57,875
Jim.

1552
01:59:57,958 --> 01:59:59,875
I'm sorry, but this
whole thing is just bizarre.

1553
01:59:59,958 --> 02:00:01,792
- You must all see...
- Now, look.

1554
02:00:01,875 --> 02:00:04,375
I really think you two
might see eye to eye

1555
02:00:04,458 --> 02:00:05,833
if you just spent
a little more time

1556
02:00:05,917 --> 02:00:07,083
getting to know each other.

1557
02:00:07,167 --> 02:00:10,375
Jim! Listen to me.

1558
02:00:10,458 --> 02:00:13,083
Come. Listen to me.

1559
02:00:16,875 --> 02:00:18,917
Come. Come here.

1560
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:20,250
I'm listening.

1561
02:00:24,375 --> 02:00:27,250
Everything that is...

1562
02:00:28,125 --> 02:00:29,458
ugly...

1563
02:00:31,417 --> 02:00:32,750
cruel...

1564
02:00:33,792 --> 02:00:35,292
stupid...

1565
02:00:36,333 --> 02:00:39,125
but most importantly, ugly.

1566
02:00:40,250 --> 02:00:44,458
Everything... is your fault.

1567
02:00:52,250 --> 02:00:54,792
- Jim! That's enough!
- You want to push me?

1568
02:00:55,583 --> 02:00:57,625
I think it's time
you went home.

1569
02:00:57,708 --> 02:00:59,583
Thank you for your insight.

1570
02:01:02,125 --> 02:01:03,333
I'm sorry.

1571
02:01:05,250 --> 02:01:06,625
He hit me.

1572
02:01:09,583 --> 02:01:11,000
I trust you.

1573
02:01:12,333 --> 02:01:14,875
I trust you, all right?

1574
02:01:20,375 --> 02:01:22,875
Ah...

1575
02:01:24,125 --> 02:01:26,125
It went well,
other than that, I think.

1576
02:01:26,208 --> 02:01:27,208
- Very well.
- Sorry.

1577
02:01:27,292 --> 02:01:28,958
- Very well indeed.
- Sorry, I...

1578
02:01:29,042 --> 02:01:31,083
- He's an idiot, though.
- Come on.

1579
02:01:50,833 --> 02:01:53,167
- I go home.
- Yeah.

1580
02:01:54,167 --> 02:01:57,583
Harrison,
you sure about this guy?

1581
02:01:58,375 --> 02:02:00,625
Look, I know
Jim lost his temper,

1582
02:02:00,708 --> 02:02:02,750
but he had a few points
back there, didn't he?

1583
02:02:03,542 --> 02:02:06,125
Look, my office
is fielding complaints

1584
02:02:06,208 --> 02:02:07,917
about plans for this place
on a daily basis,

1585
02:02:08,000 --> 02:02:09,167
more or less.

1586
02:02:09,958 --> 02:02:13,167
Jim's a Protestant.
Gives folks peace of mind.

1587
02:02:14,250 --> 02:02:16,583
People are worried
it's gonna ruin the hillside.

1588
02:02:16,667 --> 02:02:19,000
We'll do something. A little
event for the community.

1589
02:02:19,083 --> 02:02:20,083
Get them on side.

1590
02:02:20,167 --> 02:02:21,833
And don't worry,
Jim will stay on.

1591
02:02:21,917 --> 02:02:24,917
Yeah, does Jim know that?
I think he thinks he's fired.

1592
02:02:25,000 --> 02:02:27,333
I'll have Leslie telephone him
tomorrow.

1593
02:02:27,417 --> 02:02:29,250
And he can advise from afar.

1594
02:02:30,042 --> 02:02:32,417
Better for morale that way.

1595
02:02:34,375 --> 02:02:35,542
Mayor Kinney!

1596
02:02:38,458 --> 02:02:40,667
Thank you, everyone,
for being here today.

1597
02:02:47,042 --> 02:02:50,458
Girls, come in
for this picture. Here.

1598
02:03:04,000 --> 02:03:05,208
All right.

1599
02:03:05,292 --> 02:03:06,708
Right. Everybody ready?

1600
02:03:07,958 --> 02:03:11,333
Yes. Feeling lucky.

1601
02:03:11,417 --> 02:03:14,375
On the count of three.

1602
02:03:14,458 --> 02:03:17,125
Three, two, one!

1603
02:03:24,292 --> 02:03:27,750
That's a motor grader.
We used to do it with horses.

1604
02:03:27,833 --> 02:03:29,917
Makes a flat surface
to pour on.

1605
02:03:30,000 --> 02:03:31,583
Take a lot of horses

1606
02:03:31,667 --> 02:03:33,958
to do what that thing can do,
William.

1607
02:03:35,708 --> 02:03:38,125
If you want, in the morning,

1608
02:03:38,208 --> 02:03:40,625
we can take you down there
if you're curious.

1609
02:03:42,000 --> 02:03:44,750
What do you say we get you
in one of them machines?

1610
02:03:44,833 --> 02:03:46,458
Sure.

1611
02:03:46,542 --> 02:03:48,208
Big day, Mr. Tóth.

1612
02:03:50,667 --> 02:03:53,417
Yes. Yes, it is.

1613
02:03:55,542 --> 02:03:57,125
Excuse us, gentlemen.

1614
02:04:01,375 --> 02:04:04,000
Leslie mentioned during
our meeting with Jim last week

1615
02:04:04,083 --> 02:04:05,667
that you're planning
on putting your fee

1616
02:04:05,750 --> 02:04:07,333
back into the project.

1617
02:04:08,500 --> 02:04:10,917
Seems a bit irresponsible,
doesn't it,

1618
02:04:11,000 --> 02:04:12,750
given your situation?

1619
02:04:13,833 --> 02:04:16,458
Will it even last you
to the end of your commitment?

1620
02:04:21,583 --> 02:04:23,625
I will figure something out.

1621
02:04:25,625 --> 02:04:27,583
Have you discussed it
with your wife?

1622
02:04:30,750 --> 02:04:32,542
She will be supportive.

1623
02:04:34,542 --> 02:04:37,917
Suit yourself.
I wouldn't do it.

1624
02:04:39,000 --> 02:04:41,958
I know Leslie
certainly wouldn't do it.

1625
02:04:43,292 --> 02:04:44,375
I didn't want you to think

1626
02:04:44,458 --> 02:04:46,708
you'd be setting
any sort of precedent.

1627
02:04:47,875 --> 02:04:51,417
I expect nothing
from either of you.

1628
02:04:59,333 --> 02:05:00,833
How does that work?

1629
02:05:04,208 --> 02:05:08,458
The company paying themselves
a fee to finance?

1630
02:05:10,625 --> 02:05:12,375
Do you not think
I deserve to be paid

1631
02:05:12,458 --> 02:05:15,500
for the time and energy
I devote to the project?

1632
02:05:20,958 --> 02:05:22,833
Might I make a suggestion?

1633
02:05:25,167 --> 02:05:26,458
You might.

1634
02:05:28,958 --> 02:05:31,458
Your niece has made
several of our guests

1635
02:05:31,542 --> 02:05:33,375
very uncomfortable.

1636
02:05:34,333 --> 02:05:36,458
Perhaps you should
have a talk with her.

1637
02:05:38,417 --> 02:05:40,208
About what?

1638
02:05:41,917 --> 02:05:43,875
Don't get me wrong, she's...

1639
02:05:44,625 --> 02:05:47,375
she's very lovely to look at,
I know.

1640
02:05:48,208 --> 02:05:50,625
As much as we all dream
of having a little birdy

1641
02:05:50,708 --> 02:05:52,708
that keeps her trap shut,

1642
02:05:53,417 --> 02:05:56,125
comes off
like a rude affectation.

1643
02:05:57,333 --> 02:06:01,250
And I've tried to connect,
make conversation.

1644
02:06:01,833 --> 02:06:03,333
It goes nowhere.

1645
02:06:07,583 --> 02:06:10,625
Oh, it runs in the family.

1646
02:06:14,458 --> 02:06:16,583
I would like us to be friends.

1647
02:06:17,667 --> 02:06:18,667
Huh!

1648
02:06:22,667 --> 02:06:23,792
Great.

1649
02:06:25,833 --> 02:06:28,708
This is not friendly, Harry.

1650
02:06:29,917 --> 02:06:33,042
I didn't say I'd like
to slip my prick into her.

1651
02:06:41,583 --> 02:06:42,792
Forget it.

1652
02:06:45,333 --> 02:06:47,125
I had too much to drink.

1653
02:06:48,167 --> 02:06:49,375
I need a nap.

1654
02:06:53,792 --> 02:06:55,292
László?

1655
02:06:59,042 --> 02:07:00,458
We tolerate you.

1656
02:07:14,792 --> 02:07:18,208
Rub-a-dub-dub,
three maids in a tub.

1657
02:07:18,958 --> 02:07:21,375
Who do you think were there?

1658
02:07:21,458 --> 02:07:24,750
Butcher, the baker,
the candlestick maker.

1659
02:07:38,875 --> 02:07:42,250
It's invigorating, isn't it?

1660
02:07:49,500 --> 02:07:51,708
No, no.

1661
02:07:52,917 --> 02:07:54,667
Do you fancy a stroll?

1662
02:07:55,167 --> 02:07:56,167
I swear it.

1663
02:07:56,250 --> 02:07:58,583
They looked exactly
like that popular painting.

1664
02:07:58,667 --> 02:08:00,042
You know the one. Ooh!

1665
02:08:00,125 --> 02:08:02,333
Oh, stop it!

1666
02:08:02,417 --> 02:08:04,667
Daddy kept apologizing
to our hostess.

1667
02:08:04,750 --> 02:08:07,167
For context...
For context, her husband

1668
02:08:07,250 --> 02:08:08,750
was one of Van Buren
Manufacturer's

1669
02:08:08,833 --> 02:08:10,625
most important
private clients.

1670
02:08:10,708 --> 02:08:12,458
Daddy tried
to explain everything

1671
02:08:12,542 --> 02:08:13,917
that had made us late
that evening,

1672
02:08:14,000 --> 02:08:15,250
as she prepared

1673
02:08:15,333 --> 02:08:18,417
what appeared to be
a delightful-looking trifle.

1674
02:08:18,500 --> 02:08:20,250
- Was it awful?
- Yes.

1675
02:08:20,333 --> 02:08:23,708
I kid you not,
cow tallow and fruit pie.

1676
02:08:23,792 --> 02:08:27,292
No!

1677
02:08:27,375 --> 02:08:29,000
And Daddy
has such a sweet tooth.

1678
02:08:29,083 --> 02:08:31,250
I didn't know how to warn him
in front of everyone.

1679
02:08:31,333 --> 02:08:33,458
- I was starving.
- He took a bite this big.

1680
02:08:33,542 --> 02:08:35,125
I was starving!

1681
02:08:35,208 --> 02:08:38,542
He began gagging
like a house cat.

1682
02:08:41,375 --> 02:08:44,208
And all he could say
to explain was...

1683
02:08:44,292 --> 02:08:47,625
"Dear, I'm allergic."

1684
02:08:47,708 --> 02:08:49,875
"I'm allergic."

1685
02:08:49,958 --> 02:08:52,667
To which our
concerned hostess replied,

1686
02:08:52,750 --> 02:08:55,458
"Oh, goodness,
allergic to what?"

1687
02:08:55,542 --> 02:08:58,542
And he said, "To that.

1688
02:08:58,625 --> 02:09:00,917
"I am allergic
to whatever that is."

1689
02:09:10,833 --> 02:09:12,125
Oh, Daddy.

1690
02:09:18,833 --> 02:09:20,125
Let's go.

1691
02:09:22,125 --> 02:09:23,375
Bring the chair, please.

1692
02:09:31,583 --> 02:09:32,875
Zsótia.

1693
02:09:38,500 --> 02:09:39,708
You all right?

1694
02:09:42,042 --> 02:09:44,208
It has been a lovely day.

1695
02:09:44,708 --> 02:09:46,000
It certainly has been.

1696
02:09:47,125 --> 02:09:48,500
Pity the wind's
picked up a little.

1697
02:09:48,583 --> 02:09:51,500
Erzsi. It's time for us to go.

1698
02:09:52,208 --> 02:09:53,958
You won't join us for dinner
at the house?

1699
02:09:54,042 --> 02:09:56,958
Uh, we start early tomorrow.

1700
02:09:57,042 --> 02:09:58,833
Thank you for the event.

1701
02:09:58,917 --> 02:10:01,458
- Does he ever take a break?
- Never!

1702
02:10:01,542 --> 02:10:03,292
Goodbye, Mr. Van Buren.

1703
02:10:03,375 --> 02:10:04,875
All right, stay warm.

1704
02:10:06,375 --> 02:10:08,000
What's the rush?

1705
02:10:08,083 --> 02:10:09,917
We will talk at the house.

1706
02:10:15,250 --> 02:10:17,125
László, can you slow down?

1707
02:10:20,000 --> 02:10:21,500
Can you slow down?

1708
02:10:23,167 --> 02:10:26,417
I am forfeiting
the remainder of my fee

1709
02:10:26,500 --> 02:10:29,292
due to some expenses
unforeseen.

1710
02:10:30,250 --> 02:10:32,875
Oh, so that's what the son
kept alluding to.

1711
02:10:33,625 --> 02:10:35,667
Yes. He's a snake.

1712
02:10:41,208 --> 02:10:43,625
All right,
so what will that mean for us?

1713
02:10:45,000 --> 02:10:48,250
- I will figure something out.
- We will figure something out.

1714
02:10:49,333 --> 02:10:51,458
I suppose we can make do
on my salary.

1715
02:10:52,792 --> 02:10:54,167
Your salary?

1716
02:10:54,250 --> 02:10:56,417
Mr. Van Buren's helped me
with a job interview

1717
02:10:56,500 --> 02:10:58,375
in New York City.

1718
02:10:58,458 --> 02:10:59,875
I'm sure once they meet me,

1719
02:10:59,958 --> 02:11:01,792
they won't be able
to resist me.

1720
02:11:04,167 --> 02:11:06,333
Thank you
for the supper, Mrs. Tóth.

1721
02:11:06,417 --> 02:11:08,625
I thought we might
have our own little party

1722
02:11:08,708 --> 02:11:10,583
to celebrate
all of your hard work.

1723
02:11:10,667 --> 02:11:13,167
You've come so far,
the both of you.

1724
02:11:13,958 --> 02:11:16,000
Oh, it's not mine, really.

1725
02:11:16,083 --> 02:11:18,042
That's not
what László tells me.

1726
02:11:18,125 --> 02:11:21,042
He says he couldn't have
done it without you.

1727
02:11:23,708 --> 02:11:26,375
So do you have a missus
at home, Gordon?

1728
02:11:27,500 --> 02:11:29,917
Augusta passed away in '43.

1729
02:11:30,667 --> 02:11:33,250
She was sick and died
of a damn tooth infection,

1730
02:11:33,333 --> 02:11:34,792
of all things.

1731
02:11:34,875 --> 02:11:37,000
Very sorry to hear that.

1732
02:11:38,167 --> 02:11:40,583
I'm terribly sorry
for your loss.

1733
02:11:41,583 --> 02:11:43,083
He's all right.

1734
02:11:43,167 --> 02:11:45,958
He was too young then
to remember much.

1735
02:11:46,042 --> 02:11:48,458
And I was gone two years
in Arizona

1736
02:11:48,542 --> 02:11:51,292
before they shipped us all off
to Naples, Italy.

1737
02:11:51,375 --> 02:11:53,917
92nd Infantry Division.

1738
02:11:54,000 --> 02:11:57,542
They wouldn't let me back home
all that time, not once.

1739
02:11:57,625 --> 02:12:01,417
Augusta's sister looked
after him until I got back.

1740
02:12:01,500 --> 02:12:04,583
Kept me alive, though,
knowing he was waiting for me.

1741
02:12:05,708 --> 02:12:08,833
Kept me good and alive,
thank goodness.

1742
02:12:08,917 --> 02:12:11,583
Zsófia's mother passed.

1743
02:12:14,583 --> 02:12:18,417
Losing a mother,
it's an unfathomable loss.

1744
02:12:19,500 --> 02:12:21,250
To lose one's birth mother

1745
02:12:21,333 --> 02:12:24,542
is to lose the very foundation
on which we stand.

1746
02:12:26,500 --> 02:12:31,042
The mind may not know its loss
but... but the heart does.

1747
02:12:35,417 --> 02:12:36,917
I remember her.

1748
02:12:37,500 --> 02:12:39,833
That's because I've told you
so much about her.

1749
02:12:39,917 --> 02:12:41,583
You were too small.

1750
02:12:41,667 --> 02:12:43,875
No, I remember Augusta.

1751
02:12:44,375 --> 02:12:46,917
I just wanted
to make it easier on you.

1752
02:13:10,292 --> 02:13:12,000
What are you doing?

1753
02:13:16,500 --> 02:13:18,375
I'm just looking at you.

1754
02:13:20,792 --> 02:13:22,250
What do you think?

1755
02:13:23,250 --> 02:13:26,958
It's unusual, even for you.

1756
02:13:28,875 --> 02:13:30,625
- Think so?
- Hmm.

1757
02:13:31,417 --> 02:13:34,333
Many of the rooms
are quite small,

1758
02:13:34,417 --> 02:13:36,958
yet the ceilings are high.

1759
02:13:37,042 --> 02:13:38,292
Yes.

1760
02:13:39,333 --> 02:13:41,417
Inside, you must look upwards.

1761
02:13:42,333 --> 02:13:44,833
So which part of it
are we paying for?

1762
02:13:47,500 --> 02:13:49,458
The height of the ceiling.

1763
02:13:50,708 --> 02:13:52,125
The glass above.

1764
02:13:57,125 --> 02:13:58,458
I like it.

1765
02:13:59,375 --> 02:14:01,250
I'm so happy you approve.

1766
02:14:37,875 --> 02:14:40,042
The service is in here?

1767
02:14:40,125 --> 02:14:41,500
For the overflow.

1768
02:14:41,583 --> 02:14:43,500
Because of the holiday?

1769
02:14:43,583 --> 02:14:45,333
The community's growing.

1770
02:16:59,625 --> 02:17:02,958
What?

1771
02:17:03,042 --> 02:17:05,917
It's okay. It's okay.
What is happening?

1772
02:17:06,000 --> 02:17:08,167
It's too much.

1773
02:17:08,250 --> 02:17:11,875
- What is too much?
- The pain. It's too much.

1774
02:17:11,958 --> 02:17:15,292
I need Zsófia.
She has my medication.

1775
02:17:15,375 --> 02:17:18,292
Zsófia!

1776
02:17:19,167 --> 02:17:21,208
Zsófia!

1777
02:17:29,125 --> 02:17:30,417
Zsófia.

1778
02:17:35,042 --> 02:17:38,500
Get it. Go to her. Go to her.

1779
02:17:44,000 --> 02:17:47,417
Give it to her.

1780
02:17:47,500 --> 02:17:48,708
Take it.

1781
02:17:49,625 --> 02:17:51,958
I have everyone
here with me now, yes.

1782
02:17:52,792 --> 02:17:55,583
I see. Well, if there's
anything more we can do.

1783
02:17:55,667 --> 02:17:57,542
We're terribly sorry
for the news.

1784
02:17:58,708 --> 02:18:00,167
On tenterhooks at this end,

1785
02:18:00,250 --> 02:18:02,958
so give me a ring here
when you have something.

1786
02:18:04,208 --> 02:18:05,958
A big section came undone.

1787
02:18:06,042 --> 02:18:07,708
He didn't know which one
for certain.

1788
02:18:07,792 --> 02:18:09,583
And it took seven freight cars
along with it.

1789
02:18:09,667 --> 02:18:11,208
Goddamn it, Leslie!

1790
02:18:11,292 --> 02:18:12,708
How the hell do you find
these people?

1791
02:18:12,792 --> 02:18:14,292
Transport company
is our own, Dad.

1792
02:18:14,375 --> 02:18:16,125
What?

1793
02:18:16,208 --> 02:18:18,292
We sent our own guys
to Charleston.

1794
02:18:18,375 --> 02:18:20,042
The rail cars were ours too.

1795
02:18:20,125 --> 02:18:22,000
It was cheaper,
given all the back and forth.

1796
02:18:22,083 --> 02:18:23,958
It's well over
a hundred shipments, Harrison.

1797
02:18:24,042 --> 02:18:26,000
You don't utter another word
to the rail company

1798
02:18:26,083 --> 02:18:27,375
till Michael can advise.

1799
02:18:27,458 --> 02:18:29,750
I'm hoping to have some
answers for you soon, sir.

1800
02:18:31,208 --> 02:18:34,750
Can we see what can
be salvaged? How far is it?

1801
02:18:34,833 --> 02:18:37,542
The accident put two brakemen
in the hospital.

1802
02:18:37,625 --> 02:18:38,792
It's a real mess out there.

1803
02:18:38,875 --> 02:18:39,958
Send flowers to them,

1804
02:18:40,042 --> 02:18:42,042
to the families,
for Christ's sake.

1805
02:18:42,125 --> 02:18:44,708
Oh, wait, don't!
That looks guilty.

1806
02:18:44,792 --> 02:18:46,208
I'll call Michael.

1807
02:18:47,833 --> 02:18:49,708
What do you want me
to do in the meantime?

1808
02:18:49,792 --> 02:18:51,625
- With what?
- Well, our crew.

1809
02:18:53,125 --> 02:18:54,542
Let them go.

1810
02:18:54,625 --> 02:18:56,833
- You can't, sir, you cannot...
- Yes, I can!

1811
02:18:56,917 --> 02:18:59,625
Yes. Yes, I can!

1812
02:19:08,125 --> 02:19:10,042
People are gonna
write about this.

1813
02:19:10,833 --> 02:19:11,958
I'm staring down the barrel

1814
02:19:12,042 --> 02:19:14,583
of the next two goddamn years
of my life.

1815
02:19:14,667 --> 02:19:18,125
What if one of them dies?
What if they both die?

1816
02:19:19,167 --> 02:19:21,333
Who pays for it?
Are you gonna pay for it?

1817
02:19:21,417 --> 02:19:22,792
Are you gonna pay for it?

1818
02:19:23,500 --> 02:19:24,542
László,

1819
02:19:24,625 --> 02:19:25,917
in the interest
of transparency,

1820
02:19:26,000 --> 02:19:27,250
before I came to retrieve you,

1821
02:19:27,333 --> 02:19:28,792
I'd already advised
Mr. Van Buren

1822
02:19:28,875 --> 02:19:30,708
- to cut his losses...
- Shut up, Leslie!

1823
02:19:32,250 --> 02:19:34,750
Sir. Sir, please.

1824
02:19:34,833 --> 02:19:37,292
Don't beg! It's unbecoming!

1825
02:19:44,208 --> 02:19:45,458
You're welcome to stay here

1826
02:19:45,542 --> 02:19:47,375
until you find your footing
elsewhere.

1827
02:19:48,708 --> 02:19:50,333
I have a mess to clean up.

1828
02:20:03,042 --> 02:20:04,375
<i>I'm sorry, Gordon</i>

1829
02:20:05,292 --> 02:20:06,792
Don't apologize to me.

1830
02:20:06,875 --> 02:20:09,875
I will give you some money
while you look for something.

1831
02:20:09,958 --> 02:20:11,125
I'll be fine.

1832
02:20:11,875 --> 02:20:13,375
You have a kid.

1833
02:20:13,458 --> 02:20:16,667
I will give you something
and you will take it.

1834
02:20:19,667 --> 02:20:20,667
Listen...

1835
02:20:22,542 --> 02:20:23,958
you got any, uh...

1836
02:20:25,250 --> 02:20:27,167
any hop on you?

1837
02:20:27,250 --> 02:20:30,125
None at all. I'm off it.

1838
02:20:33,208 --> 02:20:34,542
Good.

1839
02:20:35,583 --> 02:20:37,250
Good. That's...

1840
02:20:38,792 --> 02:20:39,875
That's good to hear.

1841
02:20:59,708 --> 02:21:01,458
Stop it!

1842
02:21:01,542 --> 02:21:03,542
Stop it!
You're acting like a child.

1843
02:21:03,625 --> 02:21:04,625
It's over!

1844
02:21:04,708 --> 02:21:06,250
You're making me
a mess to clean up.

1845
02:21:06,333 --> 02:21:07,333
It's over!

1846
02:21:09,292 --> 02:21:11,500
You have to march over there
right now

1847
02:21:11,583 --> 02:21:13,250
and get him excited again.

1848
02:21:14,208 --> 02:21:15,833
Keep him engaged.

1849
02:21:16,500 --> 02:21:18,000
You know
how these rich fellows are.

1850
02:21:18,083 --> 02:21:19,458
For him, it's like...

1851
02:21:19,542 --> 02:21:21,083
it's like
refurbishing a kitchen.

1852
02:21:22,000 --> 02:21:24,625
Two people
are in the hospital.

1853
02:21:24,708 --> 02:21:27,250
He does not want to proceed.

1854
02:21:27,333 --> 02:21:29,000
That's not your fault!

1855
02:21:34,583 --> 02:21:36,167
It's over.

1856
02:21:37,500 --> 02:21:39,000
Over.

1857
02:21:41,083 --> 02:21:42,208
Over.

1858
02:21:43,833 --> 02:21:45,167
Finished!

1859
02:21:59,083 --> 02:22:00,542
<i>Good evening, New York,</i>

1860
02:22:00,625 --> 02:22:03,750
<i>and happy holidays
from ABC News.</i>

1861
02:22:03,833 --> 02:22:08,833
<i>November 23rd, 1958,
marks an important milestone</i>

1862
02:22:08,917 --> 02:22:10,708
<i>in the fight against the East.</i>

1863
02:22:10,792 --> 02:22:13,417
<i>This morning,
the first full-range firing</i>

1864
02:22:13,500 --> 02:22:18,500
<i>of an intercontinental
ballistic missile, or ICBM,</i>

1865
02:22:18,583 --> 02:22:20,583
<i>was conducted
by the United States.</i>

1866
02:22:21,708 --> 02:22:25,333
<i>The missile was
an AGM-65 Maverick rocket.</i>

1867
02:22:40,000 --> 02:22:44,250
All right.
Yes. I'll make a note of it.

1868
02:22:46,417 --> 02:22:47,417
Morning.

1869
02:22:47,500 --> 02:22:50,375
I'm looking for Rudolph
Heywood and Associates.

1870
02:22:51,250 --> 02:22:54,125
Pardon me, sir, but who is it
you're looking for?

1871
02:22:54,208 --> 02:22:56,792
László Tóth. He draws there.

1872
02:22:56,875 --> 02:22:58,625
Could I ask you to spell that?

1873
02:22:58,708 --> 02:23:03,375
- Yeah, it's, uh, L-A-S-L-O...
- Oh. Yes. I see him.

1874
02:23:04,000 --> 02:23:06,000
The draughtsmen
are right upstairs.

1875
02:23:06,083 --> 02:23:08,667
All righty. Thank you, ma'am.

1876
02:23:28,792 --> 02:23:30,833
<i>The Macy's
Thanksgiving Day Parade</i>

1877
02:23:30,917 --> 02:23:32,500
<i>is just around the corner,</i>

1878
02:23:32,583 --> 02:23:37,417
<i>and anticipation is building
for this annual spectacle.</i>

1879
02:23:37,500 --> 02:23:39,792
On <i>the political front,
New York...</i>

1880
02:23:56,208 --> 02:23:57,333
László?

1881
02:24:04,708 --> 02:24:05,833
László?

1882
02:24:14,708 --> 02:24:16,042
Michael.

1883
02:24:18,625 --> 02:24:20,125
We have some news.

1884
02:24:21,667 --> 02:24:23,000
As do I.

1885
02:24:23,792 --> 02:24:27,208
How exciting.
What is it, László?

1886
02:24:28,208 --> 02:24:31,042
Please. Go ahead, Zsófia.

1887
02:24:32,917 --> 02:24:34,625
We are making Aliyah.

1888
02:24:35,750 --> 02:24:38,583
- What?
- We are going to Jerusalem.

1889
02:24:39,375 --> 02:24:40,792
I heard you.

1890
02:24:40,875 --> 02:24:42,750
Binyamin has family there.

1891
02:24:42,833 --> 02:24:46,375
My older brothers relocated
with their families in 1950.

1892
02:24:46,458 --> 02:24:48,125
They became citizens.

1893
02:24:50,000 --> 02:24:52,333
Life is difficult there.

1894
02:24:53,083 --> 02:24:54,750
Have you thought this through?

1895
02:24:54,833 --> 02:24:56,667
It is our obligation.

1896
02:24:58,125 --> 02:24:59,625
To whom?

1897
02:24:59,708 --> 02:25:01,833
Our repatriation
is our liberation.

1898
02:25:01,917 --> 02:25:03,417
Oh, please...

1899
02:25:05,000 --> 02:25:06,792
Where will you live?

1900
02:25:07,792 --> 02:25:08,958
Hmm?

1901
02:25:09,042 --> 02:25:10,667
Where will you work?

1902
02:25:10,750 --> 02:25:13,667
We can stay with my brother's
family when we first arrive.

1903
02:25:14,500 --> 02:25:17,458
I was planning to help
with the baby.

1904
02:25:17,542 --> 02:25:19,792
My brother's wife can help,
also.

1905
02:25:20,917 --> 02:25:22,083
I know.

1906
02:25:23,333 --> 02:25:26,208
I am Jewish.
My child is Jewish.

1907
02:25:26,292 --> 02:25:27,667
We must go home now.

1908
02:25:27,750 --> 02:25:30,208
Does it somehow make us
less Jewish that we are here?

1909
02:25:30,292 --> 02:25:31,708
Are we not Jewish?

1910
02:25:34,583 --> 02:25:36,083
I see.

1911
02:25:38,000 --> 02:25:41,417
Perhaps Binyamin did not
recognize me to begin with.

1912
02:25:41,500 --> 02:25:42,875
He does.

1913
02:25:51,542 --> 02:25:52,792
I'm sorry.

1914
02:25:54,125 --> 02:25:55,500
No, I'm sorry.

1915
02:25:56,042 --> 02:25:57,333
I'm sorry.

1916
02:26:01,208 --> 02:26:03,000
It's wonderful news.

1917
02:26:04,500 --> 02:26:05,917
Mmm-hmm.

1918
02:26:06,000 --> 02:26:09,208
We reacted badly
out of self-interest.

1919
02:26:11,333 --> 02:26:12,833
It is simply that...

1920
02:26:14,875 --> 02:26:16,833
we are going to miss you.

1921
02:26:18,167 --> 02:26:20,292
Well, we would like you
to come.

1922
02:26:21,042 --> 02:26:23,792
Dear, we have jobs here.

1923
02:26:23,875 --> 02:26:25,458
You could have a better job
in Israel.

1924
02:26:25,542 --> 02:26:26,583
I like my job.

1925
02:26:26,667 --> 02:26:28,417
A woman's column.
It's beneath you.

1926
02:26:28,500 --> 02:26:30,708
I write for a paper
and I'm paid for it.

1927
02:26:32,083 --> 02:26:35,000
How many women my age
could make the same claim?

1928
02:26:40,542 --> 02:26:42,417
What's your news, László?

1929
02:26:45,708 --> 02:26:48,583
Harrison asked me back.

1930
02:27:03,375 --> 02:27:06,250
Michael
came by the office today.

1931
02:27:08,083 --> 02:27:11,083
Insurance monies came through.

1932
02:27:12,250 --> 02:27:14,250
They plan to for ego
the library

1933
02:27:14,333 --> 02:27:17,500
to compensate
for legal expenses, but...

1934
02:27:19,667 --> 02:27:22,000
they want to complete
the project.

1935
02:27:22,083 --> 02:27:24,208
I don't like that man.

1936
02:27:24,292 --> 02:27:25,792
You scarcely knew him.

1937
02:27:25,875 --> 02:27:28,625
He dropped you
as quickly as he took you on.

1938
02:27:28,708 --> 02:27:32,375
He's in Roma on business.

1939
02:27:32,458 --> 02:27:33,792
He would like me to join him

1940
02:27:33,875 --> 02:27:38,208
to select the marble
for the altarpiece in Carrara.

1941
02:27:38,292 --> 02:27:41,875
I told you, tor him,
it's like doing a kitchen.

1942
02:27:45,208 --> 02:27:46,208
Darling?

1943
02:27:46,292 --> 02:27:47,750
Everyone is leaving me.

1944
02:27:47,833 --> 02:27:49,542
- No, it isn't true.
- Isn't it?

1945
02:27:49,625 --> 02:27:52,000
- No.
- No, it isn't.

1946
02:27:52,083 --> 02:27:55,875
Uncle László is leaving you
only for a short time.

1947
02:27:55,958 --> 02:27:57,125
For some days.

1948
02:27:57,208 --> 02:28:00,625
And I will visit and so will
you. We will find a way.

1949
02:28:00,708 --> 02:28:02,083
I can make arrangements

1950
02:28:02,167 --> 02:28:04,542
to have you dropped and
picked up at the newspaper.

1951
02:28:04,625 --> 02:28:07,667
No. It's not just this trip.

1952
02:28:09,250 --> 02:28:11,750
You'll be in Doylestown
again now.

1953
02:28:15,167 --> 02:28:17,125
I'll be fine on my own.

1954
02:28:25,875 --> 02:28:27,583
I will make arrangements.

1955
02:28:28,792 --> 02:28:31,875
Promise you won't let it
drive you mad.

1956
02:28:37,375 --> 02:28:38,917
I promise.

1957
02:28:55,667 --> 02:28:58,500
It's time to go!
You'll be late!

1958
02:28:58,583 --> 02:29:01,208
Yes, yes. Yes, one minute.

1959
02:30:08,667 --> 02:30:11,208
I must say,
Mr. Tóth, you look a mess.

1960
02:30:13,000 --> 02:30:14,583
I would expect your Elizabeth

1961
02:30:14,667 --> 02:30:16,250
to be taking better care
of you.

1962
02:30:18,792 --> 02:30:21,500
The years have been difficult.

1963
02:30:21,583 --> 02:30:23,208
For us all.

1964
02:30:24,000 --> 02:30:25,125
For us all.

1965
02:30:26,000 --> 02:30:27,000
Huh.

1966
02:30:33,458 --> 02:30:34,917
Where the hell is he?

1967
02:30:37,792 --> 02:30:40,375
I'm sure he'll be...
be along any minute.

1968
02:30:42,500 --> 02:30:44,500
He lives in the mountains.

1969
02:30:45,458 --> 02:30:46,667
It takes time.

1970
02:30:51,000 --> 02:30:53,583
This is why I never
do business with Italians.

1971
02:30:54,333 --> 02:30:56,125
They're the spics of Europe.

1972
02:30:59,167 --> 02:31:01,208
He's right here now.

1973
02:31:04,042 --> 02:31:05,083
Finally, darling.

1974
02:31:05,167 --> 02:31:06,792
<i>Che bello.</i>

1975
02:31:11,708 --> 02:31:14,125
- Mr. Van Buren.
- Orazio.

1976
02:31:19,500 --> 02:31:20,583
Hey...

1977
02:31:22,292 --> 02:31:23,833
What happened to his hand?

1978
02:31:26,458 --> 02:31:27,875
Dangerous work.

1979
02:31:36,458 --> 02:31:38,792
I've worn the wrong
shoes for this little trek.

1980
02:31:38,875 --> 02:31:40,542
Do you mind if I take
your arm?

1981
02:31:41,458 --> 02:31:43,917
Step where I step,
you will be all right.

1982
02:33:29,792 --> 02:33:31,708
It is beautiful, no?

1983
02:33:35,583 --> 02:33:37,042
It is beautiful.

1984
02:33:39,083 --> 02:33:41,875
Exactly as you described,
László.

1985
02:33:54,458 --> 02:33:56,208
<i>Extraordinary.</i>

1986
02:34:22,875 --> 02:34:24,250
I'm so happy to see you again.

1987
02:34:24,333 --> 02:34:26,875
I am happy to see you,
old friend.

1988
02:34:26,958 --> 02:34:29,083
Such a life down the years.

1989
02:34:29,167 --> 02:34:30,792
And we are still here.

1990
02:34:47,458 --> 02:34:49,333
This is magic. Thank you.

1991
02:34:49,417 --> 02:34:51,042
László, László,

1992
02:34:51,125 --> 02:34:53,167
there will be
a big party tonight.

1993
02:34:53,250 --> 02:34:55,667
I remember how much
you love a party.

1994
02:34:56,917 --> 02:34:58,375
Yeah.

